window.BLS_DATA = {"manifest":{"id":"bls","title":"BLS — Basic Life Support","subtitle":"The Ultimate Provider Course Reviewer","version":"1.0.0","edition":"Based on the AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC","description":"A comprehensive, self-contained study reviewer for Basic Life Support. Each chapter includes a concise summary, clinical pearls, red flags, common mistakes, memory aids, decision trees, high-yield flashcards, AHA-style quiz questions, and realistic scenarios. Designed for EMTs, nurses, nursing students, paramedics, and all healthcare providers preparing for BLS Provider certification.","icon":"heart-pulse","color":"#c8102e","accentColor":"#1f6feb","estimatedHours":12,"difficulty":"Beginner to Intermediate","certification":"AHA BLS Provider","examLink":"https://cpr.heart.org/","audience":["EMT","AEMT","Paramedic","Nurse","Nursing Student","Physician","Healthcare Provider"],"prerequisites":["None — BLS is the entry-level resuscitation course"],"contentTypes":["summary","flashcards","quizzes","scenarios","algorithms","tables"],"chapters":[{"id":"c01","number":1,"title":"Chain of Survival & Systems of Care","section":"Foundations","difficulty":"Beginner"},{"id":"c02","number":2,"title":"Scene Safety, Assessment & Recognition of Cardiac Arrest","section":"Foundations","difficulty":"Beginner"},{"id":"c03","number":3,"title":"High-Quality CPR: Adult (1-Rescuer)","section":"Adult BLS","difficulty":"Beginner"},{"id":"c04","number":4,"title":"Adult 2-Rescuer CPR & Team Dynamics","section":"Adult BLS","difficulty":"Intermediate"},{"id":"c05","number":5,"title":"Automated External Defibrillation (AED)","section":"Adult BLS","difficulty":"Beginner"},{"id":"c06","number":6,"title":"Ventilation: Barrier Devices, Pocket Mask & Bag-Mask","section":"Airway & Breathing","difficulty":"Intermediate"},{"id":"c07","number":7,"title":"Breaths, Ventilations & Advanced Airway Considerations","section":"Airway & Breathing","difficulty":"Intermediate"},{"id":"c08","number":8,"title":"Child BLS","section":"Pediatric BLS","difficulty":"Intermediate"},{"id":"c09","number":9,"title":"Infant BLS","section":"Pediatric BLS","difficulty":"Intermediate"},{"id":"c10","number":10,"title":"Foreign-Body Airway Obstruction (Adult, Child, Infant)","section":"Emergencies","difficulty":"Beginner"},{"id":"c11","number":11,"title":"Opioid-Associated Life-Threatening Emergencies","section":"Emergencies","difficulty":"Intermediate"},{"id":"c12","number":12,"title":"Special Circumstances: Drowning, Pregnancy, Recovery & Post-Arrest Care","section":"Emergencies","difficulty":"Intermediate"}]},"chapters":{"c01":{"id":"c01","title":"Chain of Survival & Systems of Care","shortTitle":"Chain of Survival","estimatedStudyTime":25,"difficulty":"Beginner","learningObjectives":["Describe the purpose of the Chain of Survival and how each link contributes to survival from cardiac arrest.","List the links of the 2025 AHA universal Chain of Survival and explain why the concept was consolidated.","Differentiate the emphasis of out-of-hospital cardiac arrest (OHCA) from in-hospital cardiac arrest (IHCA).","Explain the role of the recovery link and survivorship after cardiac arrest.","Describe how a BLS provider fits into the larger system of care, including dispatcher-assisted CPR and hand-off to advanced providers.","Explain why early, high-quality CPR and rapid defibrillation are the two links most influenced by bystanders and BLS providers."],"summary":[{"title":"What the Chain of Survival Is","content":"The Chain of Survival is a metaphor describing the sequence of time-sensitive actions that give a person in cardiac arrest the best chance of survival. Each link depends on the ones before it: a delay or weakness in any single link reduces the effectiveness of the whole chain. BLS providers own the earliest and most impactful links — recognition, activation, high-quality CPR, and defibrillation."},{"title":"The 2025 Universal Chain of Survival","content":"The 2025 AHA Guidelines consolidated the previously separate adult and pediatric, in-hospital and out-of-hospital chains into a single universal six-link Chain of Survival. The links are: (1) activation of the emergency response, (2) high-quality CPR, (3) defibrillation, (4) advanced resuscitation interventions, (5) post-cardiac arrest care, and (6) recovery. A separate Neonatal Chain of Care was introduced for the newborn population."},{"title":"OHCA vs IHCA Emphasis","content":"Although the chain is now universal, the setting changes where the emphasis falls. Out-of-hospital cardiac arrest depends heavily on bystanders: recognizing arrest, calling for help, starting compressions, and using a public AED before EMS arrives. In-hospital cardiac arrest emphasizes surveillance and prevention — monitoring, rapid-response systems, and early recognition of deterioration — so that many arrests are prevented before they happen."},{"title":"The Recovery Link and Survivorship","content":"Recovery recognizes that survival does not end when a pulse returns. Survivors and their families may face physical, cognitive, and emotional challenges. The recovery link includes rehabilitation, treatment planning, psychological support, and expectations for return to daily life. It reframes cardiac arrest as a condition people survive and live beyond, not merely an event to be reversed."},{"title":"Systems of Care and the BLS Provider's Place","content":"A system of care links people, training, equipment, and organizations so that the chain functions reliably. Dispatchers coach bystanders through compressions (dispatcher-assisted CPR), BLS providers deliver high-quality CPR and defibrillation, and advanced providers add airway management, medications, and post-arrest care. Smooth hand-offs and continuous quality improvement — measuring performance and feeding it back — keep the system strong."}],"clinicalPearls":["Bystander CPR and early defibrillation are the two interventions most strongly associated with survival — and both fall squarely within BLS scope.","For every minute that defibrillation is delayed in a shockable arrest, the probability of survival falls substantially, which is why public-access AEDs matter.","Dispatcher-assisted CPR helps untrained bystanders start compressions; a BLS provider should support and integrate with this system rather than work in isolation.","The recovery link means debriefing the rescuers and supporting the family are part of good resuscitation, not optional extras."],"redFlags":["Failing to activate the emergency response system early — no help or AED is coming if no one calls.","Treating post-ROSC (return of spontaneous circulation) as the finish line and stopping monitoring or care.","A weak first link (delayed recognition) cannot be rescued by a strong later link (excellent ALS)."],"commonMistakes":["Assuming defibrillation is only an advanced-provider skill — AED use is a core BLS and public action.","Confusing the universal chain with the older separate chains; since 2025 there is one six-link chain plus a distinct newborn chain.","Overlooking prevention and surveillance as the leading emphasis for in-hospital arrests."],"memoryAids":["Think 'Call, Push, Shock' for the bystander-dependent front of the chain: activate, compress, defibrillate.","The chain is only as strong as its weakest link — speed and quality at every step.","Recovery = the sixth link; survival is a journey, not a single moment."],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"BLS Provider's Priorities Within the Chain","content":"Unresponsive person found\n  → Ensure scene is safe\n  → Check responsiveness and breathing / pulse (≤10 s)\n     → Normal breathing + pulse: monitor, position, reassess\n     → No normal breathing / no pulse: CARDIAC ARREST\n        → Activate emergency response + get AED (Link 1)\n        → Start high-quality CPR immediately (Link 2)\n        → Apply AED and defibrillate as soon as available (Link 3)\n        → Hand off to advanced providers (Link 4)\n        → Support post-arrest and recovery care (Links 5–6)"}],"references":["AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Executive Summary and Systems of Care","AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Universal Chain of Survival"]},"c02":{"id":"c02","title":"Scene Safety, Assessment & Recognition of Cardiac Arrest","shortTitle":"Assessment & Recognition","estimatedStudyTime":30,"difficulty":"Beginner","learningObjectives":["Perform a scene safety check before approaching a collapsed person.","Assess responsiveness using the tap-and-shout technique.","Activate the emergency response system and obtain an AED appropriately.","Check for breathing and a pulse simultaneously in no more than 10 seconds.","Distinguish agonal gasping from normal breathing.","State the three findings that define cardiac arrest for a BLS provider.","Explain when to begin chest compressions based on the assessment."],"summary":[{"title":"Scene Safety First","content":"Before touching a patient, ensure the scene is safe for you, the patient, and bystanders. Look for traffic, fire, electrical hazards, water, violence, or environmental dangers. A rescuer who becomes a second victim helps no one. Use personal protective equipment as available. Only approach once the scene is safe or has been made safe."},{"title":"Check Responsiveness","content":"Tap the person's shoulders firmly and shout, 'Are you okay?' A person who does not respond, move, or react is unresponsive. For infants, tap the sole of the foot instead of the shoulders. Unresponsiveness is the trigger to call for help and continue the assessment."},{"title":"Activate the Emergency Response and Get an AED","content":"If the person is unresponsive, immediately shout for nearby help and activate the emergency response system (call 911 or the facility code). Send someone to retrieve an AED and additional equipment. If you are alone with a phone, use speaker mode so you can start care while help is dispatched. Rapid activation ensures defibrillation and advanced care are already on the way."},{"title":"Check Breathing and Pulse Together (≤10 seconds)","content":"For a healthcare/BLS provider, simultaneously scan for breathing and palpate a pulse, taking no more than 10 seconds. Look for chest rise and normal breathing while feeling for a carotid pulse in adults and children, or a brachial pulse in infants. Checking both at once avoids delaying compressions. If you are unsure whether there is a pulse within 10 seconds, treat the patient as being in cardiac arrest and begin CPR."},{"title":"Agonal Gasps Are Not Breathing","content":"In the first minutes of cardiac arrest, a person may gasp occasionally. These agonal gasps are slow, irregular, sometimes snoring or gurgling efforts — they are a sign of arrest, not of adequate breathing. Do not be fooled into withholding CPR because the person 'took a breath.' Only normal, effective breathing counts as breathing."},{"title":"Recognizing Cardiac Arrest","content":"For a BLS provider, cardiac arrest is recognized by three findings: the person is unresponsive, is not breathing normally (absent breathing or only gasping), and has no definite pulse within 10 seconds. When these are present, begin high-quality CPR immediately, starting with chest compressions."}],"clinicalPearls":["When in doubt about a pulse, start compressions — the harm of compressions on a patient who has a weak pulse is far less than the harm of withholding CPR from someone in arrest.","Checking breathing and pulse at the same time keeps the pause under 10 seconds and speeds the start of compressions.","Agonal gasping is common early in arrest and is one of the most missed signs of cardiac arrest.","Use a phone on speaker so you never have to choose between calling for help and starting care."],"redFlags":["Interpreting agonal gasps as normal breathing and delaying CPR.","Spending more than 10 seconds searching for a pulse.","Approaching an unsafe scene and becoming a second casualty."],"commonMistakes":["Skipping the scene-safety check in the urgency to help.","Performing a prolonged, careful pulse check instead of a quick simultaneous assessment.","Failing to send a specific person for the AED while starting CPR."],"memoryAids":["Safety → Shout & Tap → Shout for help/Call → Check breathing & pulse → CPR.","'No response, no normal breathing, no pulse' = start CPR.","Gasping is grave — treat agonal breathing as arrest."],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"BLS Assessment and Recognition Sequence","content":"Scene safe?\n  → No: make safe or wait for it to be made safe\n  → Yes: approach\n     → Tap and shout — responsive?\n        → Yes: monitor, reassess, get help as needed\n        → No (unresponsive):\n           → Shout for help + activate emergency response + send for AED\n           → Check breathing AND pulse simultaneously (≤10 s)\n              → Normal breathing + pulse: monitor / recovery position, reassess\n              → Pulse, no normal breathing: give breaths (rescue breathing)\n              → No pulse / not breathing normally / unsure: START CPR"}],"references":["AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Adult Basic Life Support","AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — BLS Assessment and Recognition of Arrest"]},"c03":{"id":"c03","title":"High-Quality CPR: Adult (1-Rescuer)","shortTitle":"Adult 1-Rescuer CPR","estimatedStudyTime":35,"difficulty":"Beginner","learningObjectives":["State the five components of high-quality chest compressions for an adult.","Give the correct compression rate and depth for an adult.","Describe correct hand placement and body mechanics for compressions.","Explain the importance of full chest recoil and minimizing interruptions.","State the compression-to-ventilation ratio for 1-rescuer adult CPR.","Explain compression-only (hands-only) CPR and when it is used.","Define chest compression fraction and state the target."],"summary":[{"title":"The Five Components of High-Quality CPR","content":"High-quality chest compressions are the foundation of CPR. The five components are: (1) an adequate rate of 100–120 compressions per minute, (2) adequate depth of at least 2 inches (5 cm), (3) allowing full chest recoil after each compression, (4) minimizing interruptions in compressions, and (5) avoiding excessive ventilation. Getting these right does more for survival than any other single BLS action."},{"title":"Rate and Depth","content":"Compress the adult chest at a rate of 100–120 per minute — fast, but not so fast that depth suffers. Compress to a depth of at least 2 inches (5 cm) but not more than 2.4 inches (6 cm); excessive depth can cause injury without added benefit. Counting aloud or using a metronome or feedback device helps maintain rate and depth."},{"title":"Hand Placement and Body Mechanics","content":"Place the heel of one hand on the center of the chest, on the lower half of the sternum, and the other hand on top, interlocking or lifting the fingers off the chest. Position your shoulders directly over your hands, keep your arms straight, and compress using your body weight rather than your arm muscles. This delivers effective depth and reduces fatigue. Perform CPR on a firm, flat surface."},{"title":"Full Chest Recoil","content":"After each compression, release completely so the chest fully re-expands without lifting your hands off the chest. Full recoil lets the heart refill with blood between compressions. Leaning on the chest ('incomplete recoil') reduces the blood that returns to the heart and lowers the effectiveness of the next compression."},{"title":"Minimize Interruptions and Chest Compression Fraction","content":"Interruptions in compressions cause blood flow to fall rapidly. Keep any pause — for breaths, rhythm analysis, or switching rescuers — to less than 10 seconds. Chest compression fraction (CCF) is the proportion of total resuscitation time spent actively compressing; aim for at least 60%, and ideally higher. The more time hands are on the chest, the better the perfusion."},{"title":"Ratio and Compression-Only CPR","content":"For a single rescuer performing adult CPR without an advanced airway, the compression-to-ventilation ratio is 30:2 — thirty compressions followed by two breaths. If a rescuer is untrained, unable, or unwilling to give breaths, compression-only (hands-only) CPR is recommended for adults with sudden collapse: push hard and fast in the center of the chest continuously until help or an AED arrives. Any CPR is far better than none."}],"clinicalPearls":["Push to the beat of 100–120/min — the tempo of many familiar songs helps rescuers keep pace.","Let the chest come all the way back up between compressions; do not lean on the chest.","Hands-only CPR removes the barrier of mouth-to-mouth and keeps blood flowing when a rescuer will not or cannot ventilate.","Swap compressors about every 2 minutes to prevent fatigue-related loss of depth, keeping the switch under 10 seconds."],"redFlags":["Compressing too slowly, too shallow, or leaning on the chest — all reduce blood flow.","Long pauses in compressions that drop the compression fraction and perfusion.","Compressing on a soft surface (like a mattress) without a backboard, wasting depth."],"commonMistakes":["Going faster than 120/min, which sacrifices depth and recoil.","Incomplete recoil from leaning on the chest between compressions.","Interrupting compressions too long to give breaths or check for a pulse."],"memoryAids":["'Push hard, push fast, let it come back, don't stop' captures the five components.","Rate 100–120, depth 2–2.4 inches, ratio 30:2.","C-A-B: Compressions come first, then Airway, then Breathing for adults."],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"1-Rescuer Adult CPR Cycle","content":"Confirmed adult cardiac arrest\n  → Place on firm, flat surface; expose chest\n  → Hands on lower half of sternum\n  → 30 compressions: rate 100–120/min, depth 2–2.4 in, full recoil\n     → Trained and willing: open airway, give 2 breaths (each ~1 s, visible chest rise)\n     → Untrained/unwilling to ventilate: continue compression-only CPR\n  → Repeat 30:2 cycles; apply AED as soon as available\n  → Minimize interruptions (<10 s); switch compressors ~every 2 min"}],"references":["AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Adult Basic Life Support","AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — High-Quality CPR Components"]},"c04":{"id":"c04","title":"Adult 2-Rescuer CPR & Team Dynamics","shortTitle":"2-Rescuer CPR & Teams","estimatedStudyTime":30,"difficulty":"Intermediate","learningObjectives":["Describe the roles in multi-rescuer adult CPR and how they rotate.","State the adult compression-to-ventilation ratio with two rescuers.","Explain how and when to switch compressors to maintain quality.","Describe ventilation timing once an advanced airway is in place.","List the elements of effective resuscitation team dynamics.","Explain how to minimize pre-shock and post-shock pauses as a team."],"summary":[{"title":"Roles in Multi-Rescuer CPR","content":"When more rescuers are available, work is divided: one performs compressions, one manages the airway and gives breaths, one operates the AED, and a team leader coordinates. Clear role assignment prevents duplicated effort and gaps. Roles rotate so the compressor can rest, keeping compression quality high. In a small team, one person may hold more than one role, but responsibilities should still be explicit."},{"title":"Adult Ratio with Two Rescuers","content":"For an adult, the compression-to-ventilation ratio stays at 30:2 even with two rescuers (unlike children and infants, which change to 15:2 with two rescuers). One rescuer compresses while the other prepares and delivers the two breaths during the brief pause after 30 compressions, then compressions resume immediately."},{"title":"Switching Compressors","content":"Compressor fatigue reduces depth within about 2 minutes, often without the rescuer noticing. Switch the compressor role about every 2 minutes (roughly every 5 cycles of 30:2), ideally during a natural pause such as AED rhythm analysis. Plan the switch in advance and complete it in less than 10 seconds so blood flow is barely interrupted."},{"title":"Ventilation with an Advanced Airway","content":"Once an advanced airway (such as a supraglottic device or endotracheal tube placed by trained providers) is in place, rescuers no longer pause compressions for breaths. Instead, deliver continuous compressions at 100–120/min and give one breath every 6 seconds (about 10 breaths per minute). This maximizes the compression fraction while providing steady ventilation."},{"title":"Team Dynamics","content":"Effective resuscitation teams use closed-loop communication (orders are repeated back and completion confirmed), clear messages, defined roles and responsibilities, knowledge sharing, constructive intervention, reassessment and summarizing, and mutual respect. The team leader keeps the big picture, assigns tasks, monitors performance, and adjusts the plan; team members speak up if they see a problem or cannot complete a task."}],"clinicalPearls":["The adult ratio does not change with more rescuers — it stays 30:2 until an advanced airway is placed.","Anticipate the 2-minute switch so it happens smoothly during the AED analysis pause.","Closed-loop communication ('Give 2 breaths' → 'Giving 2 breaths' → 'Breaths done') prevents missed or duplicated actions.","With an advanced airway, stop pausing for breaths — compress continuously and ventilate once every 6 seconds."],"redFlags":["Long, disorganized compressor switches that create dangerous pauses.","Two rescuers both assuming someone else is doing compressions.","Over-ventilating once an advanced airway is in place."],"commonMistakes":["Changing the adult ratio to 15:2 — that ratio is only for 2-rescuer child and infant CPR.","Failing to rotate compressors, allowing depth to decay from fatigue.","Silence instead of closed-loop communication, leading to missed tasks."],"memoryAids":["Adult stays 30:2 no matter how many rescuers; kids drop to 15:2 with two.","Advanced airway = continuous compressions + 1 breath every 6 seconds (~10/min).","Team dynamics: Roles, Loops, Respect — assign, confirm, and support."],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"2-Rescuer Adult CPR Flow","content":"Two or more rescuers present\n  → Assign roles: compressor, airway/breaths, AED, leader\n  → No advanced airway: 30:2 (compressor pauses briefly for 2 breaths)\n     → Every ~2 min (5 cycles) or at AED analysis: switch compressors (<10 s)\n  → Advanced airway placed: continuous compressions + 1 breath every 6 s\n  → Throughout: closed-loop communication, minimize pauses, reassess"}],"references":["AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Adult Basic Life Support","AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Team Dynamics and Systems of Care"]},"c05":{"id":"c05","title":"Automated External Defibrillation (AED)","shortTitle":"AED","estimatedStudyTime":30,"difficulty":"Beginner","learningObjectives":["Describe the purpose of an AED and why early defibrillation improves survival.","List the steps to operate an AED safely.","Describe correct pad placement for adults and children.","Explain the pediatric considerations for AED use, including dose attenuators.","Manage special situations: wet chest, implanted devices, medication patches, hairy chest, and pregnancy.","Integrate AED use with high-quality CPR to minimize pauses."],"summary":[{"title":"What an AED Does","content":"An automated external defibrillator analyzes the heart rhythm and, if it detects a shockable rhythm (ventricular fibrillation or pulseless ventricular tachycardia), delivers an electrical shock to allow a normal rhythm to resume. Early defibrillation is one of the strongest predictors of survival in shockable arrest, and AEDs are designed for use by lay rescuers and BLS providers with minimal training."},{"title":"Operating an AED","content":"The four universal steps are: (1) Power on the AED — it will give voice prompts. (2) Attach the pads to the patient's bare, dry chest as pictured on the pads. (3) Allow the AED to analyze the rhythm — ensure no one touches the patient ('clear'). (4) If a shock is advised, ensure everyone is clear and press the shock button, then immediately resume chest compressions. Follow the device prompts throughout and continue CPR between analyses."},{"title":"Pad Placement","content":"The most common placement is anterolateral: one pad on the right upper chest below the collarbone, the other on the left lower chest along the mid-axillary line. An alternative is anteroposterior (front and back). Pads must not touch each other. For children and infants, if pads are large enough to overlap, use anteroposterior placement (one on the chest, one on the back)."},{"title":"Pediatric Considerations","content":"For children younger than 8 years, use pediatric (dose-attenuating) pads or a pediatric setting if available, which reduce the energy delivered. If pediatric pads are not available, use adult pads rather than withholding defibrillation, ensuring the pads do not touch. For infants, a manual defibrillator operated by a trained provider is preferred; if unavailable, use an AED with a dose attenuator, and if that is also unavailable, an AED with adult pads may be used."},{"title":"Special Situations","content":"Wet chest: quickly wipe the chest dry before applying pads, and move the patient off standing water. Implanted device (pacemaker/ICD): place the pad at least about 1 inch (2.5 cm) away from the visible bump. Transdermal medication patch: remove the patch and wipe the area before placing a pad. Hairy chest: press pads firmly, or quickly shave the area if a razor is available and pads will not stick. Pregnancy: use the AED normally — defibrillation is safe and indicated. Remove metal jewelry only if it lies directly under a pad."},{"title":"Integrating the AED with CPR","content":"Continue high-quality CPR while the AED is retrieved and the pads are applied — only pause for analysis and shock. Minimize the pre-shock pause by charging while compressions continue where the device allows, and resume compressions immediately after the shock without checking a pulse. The AED will prompt a rhythm re-analysis about every 2 minutes, which is also a good moment to switch compressors."}],"clinicalPearls":["Apply the AED as soon as it arrives, but never stop good compressions to go find one if you are alone with the patient — send someone else.","Immediately resume compressions after a shock; do not pause to check a pulse.","Do not withhold defibrillation from a child just because only adult pads are available — use them (without letting the pads touch).","Pregnancy is not a contraindication to defibrillation; treat the mother, and you treat the baby."],"redFlags":["Touching the patient during rhythm analysis or shock delivery.","Applying pads to a wet chest or over a medication patch.","Long pre-shock and post-shock pauses that reduce perfusion."],"commonMistakes":["Delaying pad placement to finish a cycle of compressions when the AED is ready.","Placing pads so they touch each other, especially on small children.","Checking a pulse immediately after a shock instead of resuming compressions."],"memoryAids":["AED steps: Power on → Pads on → Analyze (clear) → Shock (clear), then CPR.","'Clear!' before analyze and before shock — eyes on the whole team.","Shock, then compress — hands back on the chest immediately."],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"AED Use During Cardiac Arrest","content":"Cardiac arrest, CPR in progress, AED arrives\n  → Power on the AED; attach pads to bare, dry chest\n  → AED analyzes — ensure everyone is CLEAR\n     → Shock advised: clear, deliver shock → immediately resume compressions\n     → No shock advised: immediately resume compressions\n  → Continue CPR ~2 min → AED re-analyzes (good time to switch compressor)\n  → Repeat until ROSC or advanced providers take over"}],"references":["AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Adult Basic Life Support (Defibrillation)","AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Pediatric Basic Life Support (AED Use)"]},"c06":{"id":"c06","title":"Ventilation: Barrier Devices, Pocket Mask & Bag-Mask","shortTitle":"Ventilation Devices","estimatedStudyTime":30,"difficulty":"Intermediate","learningObjectives":["Open the airway using the head-tilt/chin-lift and jaw-thrust maneuvers.","Describe the use of barrier devices and pocket masks for ventilation.","Demonstrate correct bag-mask technique, including the E-C clamp.","State the correct volume, timing, and rate for delivering breaths.","Explain the risks of excessive ventilation and gastric inflation.","Describe when to add supplemental oxygen and airway adjuncts."],"summary":[{"title":"Opening the Airway","content":"In an unresponsive patient the tongue commonly obstructs the airway. Open it with a head-tilt/chin-lift: tilt the forehead back and lift the bony chin. If a cervical spine injury is suspected (for example, after trauma), use a jaw-thrust without head extension instead. A patent airway is required before any ventilation attempt is effective."},{"title":"Barrier Devices and Pocket Masks","content":"Barrier devices reduce direct contact during rescue breathing. A face shield is a thin barrier placed over the mouth. A pocket mask is more effective: it has a one-way valve, can be used with two hands for a good seal, and many accept supplemental oxygen. To use a pocket mask, seal it over the mouth and nose, open the airway, and deliver each breath over about 1 second while watching for chest rise."},{"title":"Bag-Mask Ventilation","content":"A bag-mask device (BVM) delivers positive-pressure ventilation and can be connected to high-flow oxygen. It is most effective with two rescuers: one holds the mask seal with both hands using the E-C clamp technique (thumb and index finger form a 'C' on the mask while the remaining fingers form an 'E' lifting the jaw), while the second squeezes the bag. Deliver each breath over about 1 second, just enough to see the chest rise."},{"title":"Volume, Timing, and Rate","content":"Each breath is delivered over about 1 second with only enough volume to produce visible chest rise — roughly 500–600 mL for an adult bag. During CPR without an advanced airway, give 2 breaths after every 30 compressions (30:2). For rescue breathing in a patient who has a pulse but is not breathing adequately, give 1 breath every 6 seconds for an adult (about 10/min). With an advanced airway, ventilate once every 6 seconds without pausing compressions."},{"title":"Avoiding Over-Ventilation and Gastric Inflation","content":"Delivering breaths too fast, too forcefully, or with too much volume raises pressure in the chest, reduces blood return to the heart, and pushes air into the stomach (gastric inflation). Gastric inflation increases the risk of vomiting and aspiration and pushes up on the diaphragm, worsening ventilation. Give slow, gentle breaths just to chest rise and avoid the urge to over-ventilate under stress."},{"title":"Oxygen and Airway Adjuncts","content":"When available, connect supplemental oxygen to the pocket mask or bag to raise the delivered oxygen concentration. Airway adjuncts such as an oropharyngeal airway (OPA) — for patients without a gag reflex — or a nasopharyngeal airway (NPA) can help keep the airway open and improve bag-mask ventilation. Routine cricoid pressure is not recommended during CPR."}],"clinicalPearls":["Two rescuers make bag-mask ventilation far more effective — one seals with both hands, one squeezes the bag.","The correct volume is 'just enough to see the chest rise' — more is harmful, not better.","Suspected spinal injury? Open the airway with a jaw-thrust, not a head-tilt.","An OPA is only for patients without a gag reflex; use an NPA if a gag reflex is present."],"redFlags":["Rapid, forceful breaths that cause gastric inflation and reduce cardiac output.","No visible chest rise — indicates a poor mask seal or an obstructed airway.","Using an OPA in a patient with an intact gag reflex, which can trigger vomiting."],"commonMistakes":["A poor mask seal from a one-handed grip, causing air leaks and inadequate breaths.","Squeezing the bag too hard and too fast under stress.","Forgetting to open the airway before ventilating."],"memoryAids":["E-C clamp: 'C' of thumb and index finger seals the mask, 'E' of three fingers lifts the jaw.","Each breath: about 1 second, just to chest rise.","Adult rescue breathing: 1 breath every 6 seconds (~10/min)."],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"Ventilation Approach","content":"Need to ventilate\n  → Open airway (head-tilt/chin-lift; jaw-thrust if spinal injury suspected)\n  → Choose device: pocket mask (add O2) or bag-mask (2 rescuers preferred)\n  → Consider adjunct: OPA (no gag reflex) or NPA (gag reflex present)\n  → Deliver each breath over ~1 s to visible chest rise\n     → No chest rise: reposition airway, improve seal, check for obstruction\n  → Match rate to context: 30:2 during CPR, or 1 breath/6 s for rescue breathing / advanced airway"}],"references":["AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Adult Basic Life Support (Ventilation)","AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Airway Management and Ventilation"]}},"flashcards":{"c01":{"chapter":"c01","cards":[{"id":"c01_fc01","question":"What is the Chain of Survival?","answer":"A metaphor for the sequence of time-sensitive actions that give a cardiac-arrest victim the best chance of survival, where each link depends on the effectiveness of the ones before it.","category":"Concepts"},{"id":"c01_fc02","question":"How many links are in the 2025 AHA universal Chain of Survival?","answer":"Six links, in a single chain that applies to adult and pediatric, in-hospital and out-of-hospital cardiac arrest.","category":"Chain of Survival"},{"id":"c01_fc03","question":"List the six links of the 2025 universal Chain of Survival.","answer":"1) Activation of emergency response, 2) High-quality CPR, 3) Defibrillation, 4) Advanced resuscitation interventions, 5) Post-cardiac arrest care, 6) Recovery.","category":"Chain of Survival"},{"id":"c01_fc04","question":"What changed about the Chain of Survival in the 2025 AHA Guidelines?","answer":"The previously separate adult/pediatric and in-hospital/out-of-hospital chains were consolidated into one universal six-link chain, and a separate Neonatal Chain of Care was introduced.","category":"2025 Updates"},{"id":"c01_fc05","question":"Which two links are most influenced by bystanders and BLS providers?","answer":"Early high-quality CPR and rapid defibrillation — the interventions most strongly linked to survival.","category":"Chain of Survival"},{"id":"c01_fc06","question":"What is emphasized first in the in-hospital (IHCA) setting?","answer":"Surveillance and prevention — monitoring and rapid-response systems that recognize deterioration early so many arrests are prevented.","category":"Systems of Care"},{"id":"c01_fc07","question":"What does the recovery link recognize?","answer":"That survival continues beyond return of a pulse; survivors may need rehabilitation, psychological support, and treatment planning, and families need support too.","category":"Recovery"},{"id":"c01_fc08","question":"What is dispatcher-assisted CPR?","answer":"Emergency dispatchers coaching bystanders over the phone to recognize arrest and perform chest compressions before EMS arrives.","category":"Systems of Care"},{"id":"c01_fc09","question":"Why does early defibrillation matter so much?","answer":"In a shockable rhythm, the chance of survival falls substantially for every minute defibrillation is delayed, so rapid AED use is critical.","category":"Defibrillation"},{"id":"c01_fc10","question":"What is a 'system of care'?","answer":"The coordinated network of people, training, equipment, and organizations that makes each link of the chain function reliably, including quality improvement.","category":"Systems of Care"},{"id":"c01_fc11","question":"Can a strong later link make up for a weak first link?","answer":"No. Delayed recognition or activation cannot be rescued by excellent advanced care later — the chain is only as strong as its weakest link.","category":"Concepts"},{"id":"c01_fc12","question":"What memory phrase captures the bystander-dependent front of the chain?","answer":"'Call, Push, Shock' — activate emergency response, start compressions, and defibrillate.","category":"Memory Aids"},{"id":"c01_fc13","question":"Which population has its own separate chain in 2025?","answer":"Newborns — the Neonatal Chain of Care, which is distinct from the universal Chain of Survival.","category":"2025 Updates"},{"id":"c01_fc14","question":"What is link 4, advanced resuscitation interventions?","answer":"The advanced care added by trained providers — airway management, medications, and treatment of reversible causes — building on high-quality CPR and defibrillation.","category":"Chain of Survival"},{"id":"c01_fc15","question":"Why are hand-offs important in a system of care?","answer":"Smooth transfer of information and care between bystanders, BLS, and advanced providers keeps interventions continuous and avoids gaps that break the chain.","category":"Systems of Care"},{"id":"c01_fc16","question":"What is quality improvement's role in the chain?","answer":"Measuring resuscitation performance and feeding it back to responders strengthens the system over time and improves future survival.","category":"Systems of Care"}]},"c02":{"chapter":"c02","cards":[{"id":"c02_fc01","question":"What must you do before approaching a collapsed person?","answer":"Ensure the scene is safe for you, the patient, and bystanders — check for traffic, fire, electrical, water, violence, or environmental hazards.","category":"Scene Safety"},{"id":"c02_fc02","question":"How do you check responsiveness in an adult or child?","answer":"Tap the shoulders firmly and shout, 'Are you okay?' No response, movement, or reaction means the person is unresponsive.","category":"Assessment"},{"id":"c02_fc03","question":"How do you check responsiveness in an infant?","answer":"Tap the sole of the infant's foot and observe for a response, rather than tapping the shoulders.","category":"Assessment"},{"id":"c02_fc04","question":"What are the three findings that define cardiac arrest for a BLS provider?","answer":"Unresponsive, not breathing normally (absent or only gasping), and no definite pulse within 10 seconds.","category":"Recognition"},{"id":"c02_fc05","question":"How long should the combined breathing-and-pulse check take?","answer":"No more than 10 seconds. Checking both simultaneously avoids delaying compressions.","category":"Assessment"},{"id":"c02_fc06","question":"Where do you check the pulse in an adult or child?","answer":"The carotid artery in the neck.","category":"Assessment"},{"id":"c02_fc07","question":"Where do you check the pulse in an infant?","answer":"The brachial artery, on the inside of the upper arm.","category":"Assessment"},{"id":"c02_fc08","question":"What are agonal gasps?","answer":"Slow, irregular, occasional gasping efforts (sometimes snoring or gurgling) that occur early in cardiac arrest — a sign of arrest, NOT of adequate breathing.","category":"Recognition"},{"id":"c02_fc09","question":"If a person in arrest is gasping, should you start CPR?","answer":"Yes. Agonal gasping is not normal breathing; treat it as cardiac arrest and begin CPR.","category":"Recognition"},{"id":"c02_fc10","question":"What should you do if you are unsure whether there is a pulse within 10 seconds?","answer":"Treat the patient as being in cardiac arrest and begin chest compressions.","category":"Recognition"},{"id":"c02_fc11","question":"What should a lone rescuer with a phone do?","answer":"Activate the emergency response using speaker mode so care can begin immediately while help is dispatched.","category":"Activation"},{"id":"c02_fc12","question":"What is the correct action if the patient has a pulse but is not breathing normally?","answer":"Provide rescue breathing (breaths) and monitor the pulse; do not start compressions if a pulse is present.","category":"Assessment"},{"id":"c02_fc13","question":"What should you do after finding an adult unresponsive?","answer":"Shout for help, activate the emergency response system, and send someone to get an AED, then check breathing and pulse.","category":"Activation"},{"id":"c02_fc14","question":"Why check breathing and pulse simultaneously?","answer":"To keep the assessment under 10 seconds and start compressions as quickly as possible when arrest is present.","category":"Assessment"},{"id":"c02_fc15","question":"What is the risk of misreading agonal breathing?","answer":"It can lead a rescuer to withhold CPR from someone truly in cardiac arrest, delaying life-saving compressions.","category":"Recognition"},{"id":"c02_fc16","question":"Why is scene safety a priority even in an emergency?","answer":"A rescuer who becomes a second victim cannot help; ensuring safety protects the rescuer and allows effective care.","category":"Scene Safety"}]},"c03":{"chapter":"c03","cards":[{"id":"c03_fc01","question":"What is the correct compression rate for adult CPR?","answer":"100 to 120 compressions per minute.","category":"High-Quality CPR"},{"id":"c03_fc02","question":"What is the correct compression depth for an adult?","answer":"At least 2 inches (5 cm) but not more than 2.4 inches (6 cm).","category":"High-Quality CPR"},{"id":"c03_fc03","question":"What are the five components of high-quality chest compressions?","answer":"Adequate rate (100–120/min), adequate depth (≥2 in), full chest recoil, minimizing interruptions, and avoiding excessive ventilation.","category":"High-Quality CPR"},{"id":"c03_fc04","question":"Where do you place your hands for adult compressions?","answer":"Heel of one hand on the center of the chest (lower half of the sternum), other hand on top, fingers interlocked or lifted off the chest.","category":"Technique"},{"id":"c03_fc05","question":"What is the compression-to-ventilation ratio for 1-rescuer adult CPR?","answer":"30 compressions to 2 breaths (30:2).","category":"Ratios"},{"id":"c03_fc06","question":"Why is full chest recoil important?","answer":"It allows the heart to refill with blood between compressions; leaning on the chest reduces venous return and lowers the effectiveness of the next compression.","category":"High-Quality CPR"},{"id":"c03_fc07","question":"What is chest compression fraction (CCF) and its target?","answer":"The proportion of resuscitation time spent actively compressing; target is at least 60%, ideally higher.","category":"High-Quality CPR"},{"id":"c03_fc08","question":"What is compression-only (hands-only) CPR?","answer":"Continuous chest compressions without rescue breaths, recommended for untrained rescuers or those unwilling/unable to give breaths to an adult in sudden collapse.","category":"Compression-Only CPR"},{"id":"c03_fc09","question":"How long should any interruption in compressions last?","answer":"Less than 10 seconds.","category":"High-Quality CPR"},{"id":"c03_fc10","question":"How often should compressors switch, and why?","answer":"About every 2 minutes (or 5 cycles) to prevent fatigue that reduces compression depth; keep the switch under 10 seconds.","category":"Technique"},{"id":"c03_fc11","question":"What surface should CPR be performed on?","answer":"A firm, flat surface; on a soft surface like a bed, use a backboard or move to the floor so depth is not wasted.","category":"Technique"},{"id":"c03_fc12","question":"What body mechanics deliver effective compressions with less fatigue?","answer":"Shoulders directly over the hands, arms straight, using body weight to compress rather than the arm muscles.","category":"Technique"},{"id":"c03_fc13","question":"What does the mnemonic C-A-B stand for in adult CPR?","answer":"Compressions, Airway, Breathing — compressions come first for adults in sudden cardiac arrest.","category":"Memory Aids"},{"id":"c03_fc14","question":"What happens if compressions are given faster than 120/min?","answer":"Depth and full recoil often suffer, reducing the effectiveness of each compression.","category":"Common Mistakes"},{"id":"c03_fc15","question":"Is hands-only CPR effective for adults?","answer":"Yes. For adults with sudden witnessed collapse, hands-only CPR can be as effective as conventional CPR in the first minutes and any CPR is far better than none.","category":"Compression-Only CPR"},{"id":"c03_fc16","question":"How can a rescuer keep the correct compression rate?","answer":"Count aloud, use a metronome, use a real-time feedback device, or compress to the beat of a familiar 100–120 bpm song.","category":"Technique"},{"id":"c03_fc17","question":"Why avoid excessive ventilation during CPR?","answer":"Over-ventilation raises intrathoracic pressure, reduces venous return and cardiac output, and risks gastric inflation.","category":"High-Quality CPR"}]},"c04":{"chapter":"c04","cards":[{"id":"c04_fc01","question":"What is the adult compression-to-ventilation ratio with two rescuers?","answer":"Still 30:2. The adult ratio does not change with more rescuers (only child/infant change to 15:2).","category":"Ratios"},{"id":"c04_fc02","question":"How often should compressors switch in multi-rescuer CPR?","answer":"About every 2 minutes (roughly every 5 cycles of 30:2), completing the switch in under 10 seconds.","category":"Technique"},{"id":"c04_fc03","question":"What are the typical roles in a resuscitation team?","answer":"Compressor, airway/ventilation, AED operator, and team leader; roles rotate to keep compressions high-quality.","category":"Team Dynamics"},{"id":"c04_fc04","question":"How is ventilation delivered once an advanced airway is in place?","answer":"Continuous compressions at 100–120/min with one breath every 6 seconds (about 10 breaths/min); no pauses for breaths.","category":"Advanced Airway"},{"id":"c04_fc05","question":"What is closed-loop communication?","answer":"The sender gives a clear order, the receiver repeats it back, and confirms when it is completed — preventing missed or duplicated actions.","category":"Team Dynamics"},{"id":"c04_fc06","question":"When is the best moment to switch compressors with minimal interruption?","answer":"During a natural pause such as AED rhythm analysis, planned in advance so the change takes under 10 seconds.","category":"Technique"},{"id":"c04_fc07","question":"List the elements of effective team dynamics.","answer":"Closed-loop communication, clear messages, clear roles/responsibilities, knowledge sharing, constructive intervention, reassessment/summarizing, and mutual respect.","category":"Team Dynamics"},{"id":"c04_fc08","question":"What does the team leader do during a resuscitation?","answer":"Keeps the big picture, assigns and monitors tasks, ensures high-quality CPR, adjusts the plan, and coordinates the team.","category":"Team Dynamics"},{"id":"c04_fc09","question":"What is 'constructive intervention'?","answer":"A team member respectfully speaking up to correct or suggest a change (e.g., 'compressions look shallow') for patient safety.","category":"Team Dynamics"},{"id":"c04_fc10","question":"Why does compressor fatigue matter even if the rescuer feels fine?","answer":"Depth quietly decreases within about 2 minutes of continuous compressions, so scheduled switching preserves quality.","category":"Technique"},{"id":"c04_fc11","question":"How many breaths per minute with an advanced airway in adult CPR?","answer":"About 10 breaths per minute — one every 6 seconds.","category":"Advanced Airway"},{"id":"c04_fc12","question":"Which age groups change to 15:2 with two rescuers?","answer":"Children (1 year to puberty) and infants (under 1 year); adults remain 30:2.","category":"Ratios"},{"id":"c04_fc13","question":"What is a danger of poor communication during multi-rescuer CPR?","answer":"Tasks may be missed or duplicated — for example, both rescuers assuming the other is compressing, leaving no one doing CPR.","category":"Common Mistakes"},{"id":"c04_fc14","question":"What should a team member do if they cannot complete an assigned task?","answer":"Speak up clearly and immediately so the leader can reassign it, rather than staying silent.","category":"Team Dynamics"},{"id":"c04_fc15","question":"Why minimize pre-shock and post-shock pauses as a team?","answer":"Long pauses around defibrillation reduce perfusion and lower the chance of a successful shock; resume compressions immediately after the shock.","category":"Defibrillation"}]},"c05":{"chapter":"c05","cards":[{"id":"c05_fc01","question":"What are the four universal steps of AED operation?","answer":"1) Power on the AED, 2) Attach pads to the bare dry chest, 3) Analyze the rhythm (clear everyone), 4) Deliver a shock if advised (clear), then immediately resume CPR.","category":"AED Operation"},{"id":"c05_fc02","question":"What rhythms will an AED shock?","answer":"Shockable rhythms: ventricular fibrillation (VF) and pulseless ventricular tachycardia (pVT).","category":"Concepts"},{"id":"c05_fc03","question":"What is the standard anterolateral pad placement?","answer":"One pad on the right upper chest below the collarbone; the other on the left lower chest along the mid-axillary line.","category":"Pad Placement"},{"id":"c05_fc04","question":"What should you do immediately after delivering a shock?","answer":"Resume chest compressions immediately, without pausing to check a pulse.","category":"AED Operation"},{"id":"c05_fc05","question":"What pads/setting are used for a child under 8 years?","answer":"Pediatric (dose-attenuating) pads or a pediatric setting if available; if not, use adult pads rather than withhold defibrillation, ensuring pads don't touch.","category":"Pediatric"},{"id":"c05_fc06","question":"What is the preferred defibrillation approach for an infant?","answer":"A manual defibrillator operated by a trained provider is preferred; if unavailable, an AED with a dose attenuator; if that is unavailable, an AED with adult pads may be used.","category":"Pediatric"},{"id":"c05_fc07","question":"How do you manage a wet chest before applying AED pads?","answer":"Quickly wipe the chest dry and move the patient away from standing water so the shock is delivered effectively and safely.","category":"Special Situations"},{"id":"c05_fc08","question":"How do you place a pad near an implanted pacemaker or ICD?","answer":"Place the pad at least about 1 inch (2.5 cm) away from the visible device bump.","category":"Special Situations"},{"id":"c05_fc09","question":"What do you do about a transdermal medication patch under a pad site?","answer":"Remove the patch and wipe the area before applying the pad, to prevent burns and interference.","category":"Special Situations"},{"id":"c05_fc10","question":"How do you handle a very hairy chest for AED pads?","answer":"Press the pads firmly; if they won't stick, quickly shave the area if a razor is available, then apply new pads.","category":"Special Situations"},{"id":"c05_fc11","question":"Is defibrillation safe in pregnancy?","answer":"Yes. Use the AED normally — defibrillation is safe and indicated; treating the mother is the best treatment for the fetus.","category":"Special Situations"},{"id":"c05_fc12","question":"Why must no one touch the patient during analysis and shock?","answer":"Contact can interfere with rhythm analysis and expose rescuers to the shock; call 'Clear!' and confirm before analysis and before shocking.","category":"Safety"},{"id":"c05_fc13","question":"Should you stop CPR to look for an AED if you are alone with the patient?","answer":"No — continue high-quality CPR and send someone else for the AED; only pause for analysis and shock once it arrives.","category":"Integration"},{"id":"c05_fc14","question":"How often does an AED prompt a rhythm re-analysis?","answer":"About every 2 minutes, which is also a good time to switch compressors.","category":"Integration"},{"id":"c05_fc15","question":"What must you avoid when placing pads on a small child?","answer":"Letting the two pads touch each other; if they would overlap, use anteroposterior (front and back) placement.","category":"Pediatric"},{"id":"c05_fc16","question":"Why is early defibrillation so important?","answer":"For shockable rhythms, the chance of survival falls with each minute of delay, so shocking as early as possible greatly improves outcomes.","category":"Concepts"}]},"c06":{"chapter":"c06","cards":[{"id":"c06_fc01","question":"How do you open the airway in a patient with no suspected spinal injury?","answer":"Head-tilt/chin-lift: tilt the forehead back and lift the bony part of the chin.","category":"Airway"},{"id":"c06_fc02","question":"How do you open the airway when a spinal injury is suspected?","answer":"Use a jaw-thrust maneuver without extending the head/neck.","category":"Airway"},{"id":"c06_fc03","question":"What is the E-C clamp technique?","answer":"For mask seal: the thumb and index finger form a 'C' pressing the mask down, while the other three fingers form an 'E' lifting the jaw into the mask.","category":"Bag-Mask"},{"id":"c06_fc04","question":"How long should each breath be delivered over?","answer":"About 1 second, with just enough volume to produce visible chest rise.","category":"Technique"},{"id":"c06_fc05","question":"Why is bag-mask ventilation more effective with two rescuers?","answer":"One rescuer can maintain a tight two-handed mask seal while the other squeezes the bag, greatly improving delivered volume.","category":"Bag-Mask"},{"id":"c06_fc06","question":"What is the adult rescue-breathing rate for a patient with a pulse but inadequate breathing?","answer":"1 breath every 6 seconds (about 10 breaths per minute).","category":"Rates"},{"id":"c06_fc07","question":"What is the danger of over-ventilation?","answer":"It raises intrathoracic pressure (reducing venous return and cardiac output) and causes gastric inflation, increasing vomiting and aspiration risk.","category":"Risks"},{"id":"c06_fc08","question":"What is a pocket mask and its advantage over a face shield?","answer":"A pocket mask has a one-way valve and allows a two-handed seal and supplemental oxygen, giving more effective and protected ventilation than a thin face shield.","category":"Barrier Devices"},{"id":"c06_fc09","question":"When is an oropharyngeal airway (OPA) appropriate?","answer":"Only in patients without a gag reflex; it can trigger vomiting in a patient who still has one.","category":"Adjuncts"},{"id":"c06_fc10","question":"When is a nasopharyngeal airway (NPA) useful?","answer":"When an airway adjunct is needed but the patient may have a gag reflex; the NPA is better tolerated than an OPA.","category":"Adjuncts"},{"id":"c06_fc11","question":"What does no visible chest rise during ventilation suggest?","answer":"A poor mask seal or an obstructed/unopened airway — reposition the airway, improve the seal, and check for obstruction.","category":"Troubleshooting"},{"id":"c06_fc12","question":"Approximately what tidal volume produces chest rise in an adult?","answer":"Roughly 500–600 mL — 'just enough to see the chest rise,' not a full forceful squeeze.","category":"Technique"},{"id":"c06_fc13","question":"Is routine cricoid pressure recommended during CPR?","answer":"No, routine cricoid pressure is not recommended during CPR.","category":"Technique"},{"id":"c06_fc14","question":"How does supplemental oxygen fit into BLS ventilation?","answer":"When available, connect oxygen to the pocket mask or bag to raise the delivered oxygen concentration.","category":"Oxygen"},{"id":"c06_fc15","question":"During CPR without an advanced airway, what is the breath pattern?","answer":"2 breaths after every 30 compressions (30:2), each over about 1 second with visible chest rise.","category":"Rates"},{"id":"c06_fc16","question":"What must you always do before attempting to ventilate?","answer":"Open the airway; without a patent airway, breaths will not reach the lungs effectively.","category":"Airway"}]}},"quizzes":{"c01":{"chapter":"c01","questions":[{"id":"c01_q01","question":"How many links make up the 2025 AHA universal Chain of Survival?","options":["A. Four","B. Five","C. Six","D. Seven"],"correct":2,"rationale":"The 2025 Guidelines consolidated the separate adult/pediatric and in-hospital/out-of-hospital chains into a single universal six-link Chain of Survival. A separate seven-step-style Neonatal Chain of Care exists for newborns, but the universal chain itself has six links.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q02","question":"Which change did the 2025 AHA Guidelines make to the Chain of Survival?","options":["A. Removed the defibrillation link","B. Consolidated the separate chains into one universal chain and added a distinct newborn chain","C. Reduced the number of links to four","D. Eliminated the recovery link","E. Made bystander CPR optional"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The 2025 update merged the previously separate adult, pediatric, in-hospital, and out-of-hospital chains into a single universal Chain of Survival, and introduced a separate Neonatal Chain of Care for newborns.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q03","question":"Which two interventions, both within BLS scope, are most strongly associated with survival from cardiac arrest?","options":["A. Advanced airway placement and epinephrine","B. Early high-quality CPR and rapid defibrillation","C. IV access and 12-lead ECG","D. Targeted temperature management and coronary angiography"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Early bystander CPR and rapid defibrillation are the interventions most strongly linked to survival, and both are core BLS actions available before advanced providers arrive.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q04","question":"In the in-hospital cardiac arrest (IHCA) setting, which emphasis is placed at the front of the system of care?","options":["A. Public-access AED programs","B. Surveillance and prevention with rapid-response systems","C. Bystander recognition by untrained laypeople","D. Dispatcher-assisted CPR"],"correct":1,"rationale":"In hospitals, surveillance, monitoring, and rapid-response systems aim to recognize deterioration early and prevent many arrests before they occur, unlike the bystander-dependent front of out-of-hospital arrest.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q05","question":"What does the recovery link of the Chain of Survival address?","options":["A. Only the immediate minutes after ROSC in the field","B. Physical, cognitive, and emotional rehabilitation and support for survivors and families after arrest","C. Replacing defibrillator pads after use","D. Documentation and billing for the resuscitation"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The recovery link recognizes that survival continues beyond return of a pulse; survivors may need rehabilitation, psychological support, and treatment planning, and families need support as well.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q06","question":"A bystander calls 911 and the dispatcher coaches them to push hard and fast on the chest. This is an example of:","options":["A. Advanced cardiac life support","B. Dispatcher-assisted CPR","C. Post-cardiac arrest care","D. The recovery link"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Dispatcher-assisted CPR is when emergency dispatchers coach bystanders over the phone to recognize arrest and begin chest compressions before EMS arrives — a key part of the system of care.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q07","question":"Why is the 'weakest link' concept important in the Chain of Survival?","options":["A. Because only one link needs to work for survival","B. Because a delay or failure in any single link reduces the effectiveness of the entire chain","C. Because advanced care can always compensate for delayed CPR","D. Because the links can be performed in any order"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Each link depends on the ones before it. A weak or delayed link — such as late recognition — cannot be fully rescued by strong later care, so speed and quality matter at every step.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q08","question":"Which of the following is the FIRST link of the universal Chain of Survival?","options":["A. Defibrillation","B. High-quality CPR","C. Activation of the emergency response","D. Post-cardiac arrest care"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Activation of the emergency response is the first link — without calling for help and summoning an AED and advanced providers, the later links cannot occur.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q09","question":"Roughly what happens to survival probability for each minute defibrillation is delayed in a shockable arrest without CPR?","options":["A. It increases","B. It stays the same","C. It falls substantially","D. It is unaffected by time"],"correct":2,"rationale":"In a shockable rhythm, survival probability declines substantially with each minute defibrillation is delayed, which is the rationale for public-access AED programs and rapid AED use.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q10","question":"Which population is served by a separate chain introduced in the 2025 Guidelines?","options":["A. Geriatric patients","B. Newborns (Neonatal Chain of Care)","C. Trauma patients","D. Pregnant patients"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The 2025 Guidelines introduced a distinct Neonatal Chain of Care for newborns, separate from the universal Chain of Survival used for other populations.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q11","question":"A patient regains a pulse (ROSC) after CPR and defibrillation. What is the correct BLS mindset?","options":["A. The resuscitation is complete and no further care is needed","B. Continue monitoring and support post-arrest care; recovery is part of the chain","C. Remove the AED pads immediately and reassure the family it is over","D. Stop reassessing because the pulse has returned"],"correct":1,"rationale":"ROSC is not the finish line. Post-cardiac arrest care (link 5) and recovery (link 6) follow; the patient still needs close monitoring, support, and continued care.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q12","question":"Which statement about defibrillation and BLS scope is TRUE?","options":["A. Defibrillation with an AED is exclusively an advanced-provider skill","B. AED use is a core BLS and public-access action available to lay rescuers","C. Only physicians may apply an AED","D. AEDs should only be used after epinephrine is given"],"correct":1,"rationale":"AED use is intentionally designed for lay rescuers and BLS providers. Public-access defibrillation is a cornerstone of the chain and does not require advanced training.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q13","question":"What is the primary purpose of continuous quality improvement within a system of care?","options":["A. To assign blame after unsuccessful resuscitations","B. To measure resuscitation performance and feed it back so future outcomes improve","C. To reduce the number of AEDs in public places","D. To replace bystander CPR with technology"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Quality improvement measures performance (such as compression quality and time to defibrillation) and feeds it back to responders and the system, strengthening the chain and improving future survival.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q14","question":"Link 4 of the universal chain, advanced resuscitation interventions, includes which of the following?","options":["A. Recognizing the arrest","B. Airway management, medications, and treating reversible causes by trained providers","C. Applying the first AED shock","D. Coaching a bystander over the phone"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Advanced resuscitation interventions build on high-quality CPR and defibrillation, adding advanced airway management, medications, and treatment of reversible causes delivered by trained providers.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q15","question":"Which sequence best represents a BLS provider's priorities when finding an unresponsive, pulseless adult?","options":["A. Start an IV, then call for help, then compress","B. Activate emergency response and get an AED, start high-quality CPR, defibrillate when available","C. Perform a detailed head-to-toe exam before compressions","D. Wait for advanced providers before doing anything"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The BLS priority sequence is to activate the emergency response and obtain an AED, begin high-quality compressions immediately, and defibrillate as soon as the AED is available — the front links of the chain.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c01_q16","question":"Why did the AHA move from multiple chains to a single universal Chain of Survival in 2025?","options":["A. To make resuscitation harder to teach","B. To simplify and unify the concept across ages and settings while keeping setting-specific emphasis","C. Because defibrillation is no longer recommended","D. To eliminate the role of bystanders"],"correct":1,"rationale":"A single universal chain simplifies teaching and unifies the core sequence across adult, pediatric, in-hospital, and out-of-hospital arrest, while the emphasis (e.g., prevention in hospitals vs. bystander action in the community) still varies by setting.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c01_q17","question":"A hospital rapid-response team is called for a deteriorating patient before any arrest occurs. Which link/emphasis does this represent?","options":["A. Recovery","B. Surveillance and prevention (IHCA emphasis)","C. Defibrillation","D. Post-cardiac arrest care"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Rapid-response and early-warning systems reflect the surveillance-and-prevention emphasis of the in-hospital setting, aiming to prevent arrest by recognizing and treating deterioration early.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q18","question":"Which of the following best describes why public-access AED placement is emphasized?","options":["A. AEDs replace the need for CPR","B. Rapid defibrillation before EMS arrival improves survival in shockable arrests","C. AEDs are only useful in hospitals","D. Public AEDs are meant for training, not real use"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Because survival in shockable rhythms declines with each minute of delay, placing AEDs where the public can reach them enables defibrillation before EMS arrives, strengthening a critical link.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q19","question":"The recovery link implies that good resuscitation practice ALSO includes:","options":["A. Stopping all follow-up once ROSC is achieved","B. Supporting survivors and families and debriefing rescuers","C. Avoiding any discussion of the event with the family","D. Immediately discharging the patient"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The recovery link reframes survival as an ongoing journey, so supporting survivors and families and debriefing the rescue team are part of complete, high-quality resuscitation care.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q20","question":"Which statement about the relationship between links is MOST accurate?","options":["A. Links can be skipped without affecting outcome","B. Each link builds on and depends upon the previous links","C. The last link is the only one that matters","D. Bystander links are unimportant if EMS is nearby"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The chain is sequential and interdependent: each link builds on the ones before it, so timely, high-quality performance of the early links sets up the success of the later ones.","difficulty":"Easy"}]},"c02":{"chapter":"c02","questions":[{"id":"c02_q01","question":"What is the FIRST action when you come upon a person who has suddenly collapsed?","options":["A. Begin chest compressions","B. Check the pulse","C. Ensure the scene is safe","D. Apply an AED"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Scene safety comes first. A rescuer who is injured cannot help the patient, so you must confirm the scene is safe before approaching and assessing.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c02_q02","question":"How should you check responsiveness in an adult?","options":["A. Shake vigorously and lift the head","B. Tap the shoulders and shout, 'Are you okay?'","C. Perform a sternal rub only","D. Tap the sole of the foot"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Tapping the shoulders firmly and shouting is the standard method to assess responsiveness in adults and children. Tapping the sole of the foot is used for infants.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c02_q03","question":"For a BLS provider, the combined check for breathing and pulse should take no longer than:","options":["A. 5 seconds","B. 10 seconds","C. 30 seconds","D. 60 seconds"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The breathing and pulse check should be simultaneous and take no more than 10 seconds so compressions are not delayed.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c02_q04","question":"You find an unresponsive adult who is taking occasional slow, gasping breaths and has no pulse you can feel. What does the gasping indicate?","options":["A. The patient is breathing normally and does not need CPR","B. Agonal gasping — a sign of cardiac arrest; begin CPR","C. The patient is choking","D. The patient is recovering"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Occasional gasping is agonal breathing, a common early sign of cardiac arrest. It is not adequate breathing; CPR should begin immediately.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c02_q05","question":"Which three findings define cardiac arrest for a BLS provider?","options":["A. Chest pain, sweating, and nausea","B. Unresponsive, not breathing normally, and no definite pulse within 10 seconds","C. Confusion, low blood pressure, and fast pulse","D. Unresponsive, snoring, and a strong pulse"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Cardiac arrest is recognized by unresponsiveness, absence of normal breathing (no breathing or only gasping), and no definite pulse within 10 seconds.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c02_q06","question":"Where do you palpate the pulse in an unresponsive infant?","options":["A. Carotid artery","B. Radial artery","C. Brachial artery","D. Femoral artery only"],"correct":2,"rationale":"The brachial artery on the inner upper arm is used for infants because the short, chubby neck makes the carotid difficult to locate.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c02_q07","question":"If you cannot definitely feel a pulse within 10 seconds in an unresponsive, non-breathing patient, you should:","options":["A. Continue searching for the pulse for another 30 seconds","B. Assume there is a pulse and only give breaths","C. Begin chest compressions and treat as cardiac arrest","D. Wait for advanced providers"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Uncertainty about a pulse within 10 seconds should be treated as cardiac arrest. Beginning compressions avoids a dangerous delay; the risk of compressing a patient with a faint pulse is low.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c02_q08","question":"A lone rescuer with a mobile phone finds an unresponsive adult. What is the best way to activate help while starting care?","options":["A. Leave the patient to find a landline","B. Call emergency services on speaker mode and stay with the patient","C. Wait until after 2 minutes of CPR to call","D. Text a friend to call for you"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Using speaker mode lets a lone rescuer activate the emergency response and receive dispatcher guidance without leaving the patient or delaying care.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c02_q09","question":"An unresponsive patient has a definite pulse but is not breathing normally. What is the correct BLS action?","options":["A. Begin chest compressions","B. Provide rescue breathing (breaths) and monitor the pulse","C. Apply an AED and shock","D. Place in the recovery position and leave"],"correct":1,"rationale":"A pulse with inadequate breathing calls for rescue breathing, not compressions. Compressions are reserved for patients without a pulse. Reassess the pulse regularly.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c02_q10","question":"Why should the breathing check and pulse check be done at the same time?","options":["A. To make the assessment more thorough and slower","B. To minimize delay and keep the total pause to 10 seconds or less","C. Because breathing cannot be assessed alone","D. To avoid using an AED"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Simultaneous assessment keeps the pause short (≤10 seconds), so high-quality compressions can begin quickly if the patient is in arrest.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c02_q11","question":"Which of the following is TRUE about agonal gasps?","options":["A. They indicate adequate ventilation","B. They mean CPR should be withheld","C. They are a sign of cardiac arrest and CPR should begin","D. They only occur in choking"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Agonal gasps are irregular, ineffective breaths seen early in arrest. They are a recognition cue for cardiac arrest, and CPR should be started.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c02_q12","question":"After confirming an adult is unresponsive, what should you do BEFORE checking breathing and pulse if help is available?","options":["A. Nothing — check breathing and pulse first","B. Shout for help, activate the emergency response, and send someone for an AED","C. Start an IV","D. Perform a head-to-toe exam"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Once unresponsiveness is confirmed, immediately shout for help, activate the emergency response, and dispatch someone for an AED so defibrillation and advanced care are en route before you complete the assessment.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c02_q13","question":"Which scene hazard would make it UNSAFE to immediately approach a collapsed patient?","options":["A. A quiet living room","B. Downed electrical wires near the patient","C. A well-lit hallway","D. A grassy park"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Downed electrical wires pose a lethal hazard. The scene must be made safe (e.g., power secured) before approaching, or the rescuer risks becoming a second victim.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c02_q14","question":"A patient is unresponsive with normal breathing and a strong pulse after a fainting episode. What is the most appropriate BLS action?","options":["A. Begin chest compressions","B. Provide rescue breaths","C. Monitor, consider the recovery position, and reassess","D. Apply an AED and analyze"],"correct":2,"rationale":"A patient breathing normally with a pulse is not in arrest. Monitoring, positioning to protect the airway, and reassessing are appropriate; CPR and AED are not indicated.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c02_q15","question":"What is the main danger of a prolonged, careful pulse check in a suspected arrest?","options":["A. It uses too much equipment","B. It delays the start of chest compressions","C. It is uncomfortable for the rescuer","D. It requires two rescuers"],"correct":1,"rationale":"A prolonged pulse check delays compressions. Every second without compressions in arrest reduces the chance of survival, so the check is limited to 10 seconds.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c02_q16","question":"You witness an adult collapse and are certain the scene is safe. The patient is unresponsive, not breathing, and pulseless. What is the correct order of your next actions?","options":["A. Start compressions, then never call for help","B. Activate emergency response/get AED, then immediately begin high-quality chest compressions","C. Give 2 breaths, then check the pulse for 30 seconds","D. Place in recovery position, then call for help"],"correct":1,"rationale":"For a witnessed arrest, activate the emergency response and get an AED, then start high-quality compressions immediately. This aligns with the front links of the Chain of Survival.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c02_q17","question":"Which finding, by itself, is NOT sufficient to diagnose cardiac arrest?","options":["A. Unresponsiveness alone","B. Unresponsive plus no breathing plus no pulse","C. No pulse plus no normal breathing in an unresponsive patient","D. Agonal breathing in an unresponsive, pulseless patient"],"correct":0,"rationale":"Unresponsiveness alone can occur in fainting, seizure, or intoxication. Cardiac arrest requires unresponsiveness together with absent normal breathing and no pulse.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c02_q18","question":"Why is it acceptable to start compressions on a patient who might have a very weak pulse?","options":["A. Because compressions are harmless in all cases","B. Because the harm of delaying CPR in true arrest outweighs the low risk of compressing a patient with a faint pulse","C. Because a weak pulse always means arrest","D. Because pulse checks are never accurate"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Studies show rescuers are unreliable at detecting a weak pulse quickly. The danger of withholding CPR from someone in arrest is far greater than the minor risk of compressing a patient with a faint pulse, so uncertainty defaults to starting CPR.","difficulty":"Hard"}]},"c03":{"chapter":"c03","questions":[{"id":"c03_q01","question":"What is the recommended chest compression rate for an adult?","options":["A. 60–80 per minute","B. 80–100 per minute","C. 100–120 per minute","D. 120–140 per minute"],"correct":2,"rationale":"The AHA recommends compressing at 100–120 per minute. Slower rates provide inadequate circulation, and faster rates tend to reduce depth and full recoil.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c03_q02","question":"What is the correct compression depth for an adult?","options":["A. At least 1 inch","B. At least 2 inches (5 cm), not exceeding 2.4 inches (6 cm)","C. At least 3 inches","D. Exactly 1.5 inches"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Adult compressions should be at least 2 inches (5 cm) deep but not more than 2.4 inches (6 cm), as excessive depth can cause injury without improving outcomes.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c03_q03","question":"What is the compression-to-ventilation ratio for single-rescuer adult CPR without an advanced airway?","options":["A. 15:2","B. 30:2","C. 5:1","D. 15:1"],"correct":1,"rationale":"A single rescuer performs adult CPR at 30 compressions to 2 breaths (30:2).","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c03_q04","question":"Which of the following is NOT one of the five components of high-quality CPR?","options":["A. Adequate compression rate","B. Full chest recoil","C. Delivering rapid, deep breaths as often as possible","D. Minimizing interruptions"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Avoiding excessive ventilation is a component of high-quality CPR. Rapid, deep, frequent breaths are harmful — they raise intrathoracic pressure and reduce cardiac output.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c03_q05","question":"Why is full chest recoil between compressions important?","options":["A. It lets the rescuer rest","B. It allows the heart to refill with blood, improving the next compression","C. It increases the compression rate","D. It prevents rib fractures"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Allowing the chest to fully re-expand lets blood return to the heart. Leaning on the chest (incomplete recoil) reduces venous return and lowers cardiac output.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c03_q06","question":"Where should the hands be placed for adult chest compressions?","options":["A. Over the upper sternum","B. On the lower half of the sternum, center of the chest","C. Over the left nipple","D. On the xiphoid process"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The heel of the hand goes on the center of the chest, on the lower half of the sternum. Compressing over the xiphoid or too high reduces effectiveness and risks injury.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c03_q07","question":"What is the minimum target chest compression fraction (CCF)?","options":["A. At least 20%","B. At least 40%","C. At least 60%","D. Exactly 100%"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Aim for a compression fraction of at least 60% — the proportion of resuscitation time spent actively compressing — with higher being better.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c03_q08","question":"A bystander is untrained and unwilling to give mouth-to-mouth to an adult in sudden cardiac arrest. What should they do?","options":["A. Do nothing until EMS arrives","B. Perform compression-only (hands-only) CPR continuously","C. Only give breaths","D. Perform 15:2 CPR"],"correct":1,"rationale":"For adults with sudden collapse, compression-only CPR is recommended when a rescuer is untrained or unwilling to ventilate. Continuous compressions maintain circulation, and any CPR is far better than none.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c03_q09","question":"How long should a pause in compressions (e.g., to give breaths) ideally last?","options":["A. Less than 10 seconds","B. About 30 seconds","C. About 1 minute","D. As long as needed"],"correct":0,"rationale":"Interruptions should be kept under 10 seconds because blood flow falls quickly when compressions stop and takes time to rebuild.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c03_q10","question":"How frequently should rescuers switch the compressor role when possible?","options":["A. Every 30 seconds","B. About every 2 minutes","C. Every 10 minutes","D. Only when exhausted"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Switching about every 2 minutes (roughly every 5 cycles of 30:2) prevents fatigue that quietly reduces compression depth. The switch should take less than 10 seconds.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c03_q11","question":"A patient in cardiac arrest is on a soft mattress. What should the rescuer do to ensure effective compressions?","options":["A. Compress harder to make up for the mattress","B. Place a backboard under the patient or move them to the floor","C. Elevate the head of the bed","D. Nothing — the mattress does not matter"],"correct":1,"rationale":"A soft surface absorbs compression depth. Using a firm backboard or moving the patient to the floor ensures the force reaches the chest and achieves adequate depth.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c03_q12","question":"Which body mechanics help deliver effective compressions while reducing fatigue?","options":["A. Bent elbows and pushing with the arms","B. Shoulders over the hands, arms straight, using body weight","C. Kneeling far from the patient","D. Compressing with the fingertips"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Positioning the shoulders directly over the hands with straight arms lets the rescuer use body weight, delivering consistent depth with less fatigue than pushing with arm muscles.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c03_q13","question":"What is the danger of compressing faster than 120 per minute?","options":["A. It improves circulation with no downside","B. It often reduces depth and prevents full recoil","C. It is impossible to do","D. It increases the compression fraction"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Excessive rate typically comes at the cost of inadequate depth and incomplete recoil, both of which reduce the effectiveness of CPR.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c03_q14","question":"In the adult CPR sequence, which comes first?","options":["A. Airway","B. Breathing","C. Compressions","D. Defibrillation always before compressions"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Adult CPR follows C-A-B: compressions first, then airway, then breathing, because circulating existing oxygenated blood is the immediate priority in sudden cardiac arrest.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c03_q15","question":"Each rescue breath during CPR should be delivered:","options":["A. As forcefully as possible","B. Over about 1 second, just enough to produce visible chest rise","C. Over 5 seconds each","D. Continuously without pausing compressions in basic CPR"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Each breath is given over about 1 second with just enough volume to make the chest visibly rise. Larger or faster breaths cause gastric inflation and reduce circulation.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c03_q16","question":"Why does avoiding excessive ventilation matter during CPR?","options":["A. It saves oxygen for later","B. Over-ventilation raises intrathoracic pressure, reducing venous return and cardiac output","C. It makes compressions unnecessary","D. It has no physiological effect"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Excessive ventilation increases pressure in the chest, impeding blood return to the heart and lowering the output generated by compressions, and can also cause gastric inflation.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c03_q17","question":"A lone rescuer has performed 5 cycles of 30:2 and is becoming fatigued, with another trained rescuer now present. What is the best action?","options":["A. Continue alone to avoid interrupting compressions","B. Switch compressors quickly (in under 10 seconds) to maintain depth","C. Stop CPR entirely","D. Slow the rate to rest"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Fatigue degrades compression quality within a couple of minutes. Swapping compressors quickly maintains depth and rate while keeping the interruption minimal.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c03_q18","question":"Which statement best reflects the priority of high-quality compressions?","options":["A. Perfect breaths matter more than compressions","B. High-quality compressions with minimal interruption are the single most important BLS action","C. Compressions can be shallow if fast","D. Interruptions do not affect outcome"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Delivering compressions of adequate rate and depth with full recoil and minimal interruption drives perfusion and is the most important determinant of BLS success.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c03_q19","question":"A rescuer notices they are leaning on the chest between compressions. What problem does this cause?","options":["A. Excessive depth","B. Incomplete recoil, reducing venous return and CPR effectiveness","C. Too high a compression rate","D. Nothing significant"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Leaning prevents the chest from fully re-expanding (incomplete recoil), which limits the blood refilling the heart and weakens the next compression.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c03_q20","question":"When is compression-only CPR specifically recommended over conventional CPR?","options":["A. For all pediatric arrests","B. For adults in sudden collapse when a rescuer is untrained or unwilling/unable to give breaths","C. For all drowning victims","D. Never"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Compression-only CPR is recommended for adult sudden collapse when rescuers cannot or will not ventilate. Note that ventilation is more important in children, infants, and drowning, where breaths should be included when possible.","difficulty":"Hard"}]},"c04":{"chapter":"c04","questions":[{"id":"c04_q01","question":"What is the compression-to-ventilation ratio for 2-rescuer ADULT CPR without an advanced airway?","options":["A. 15:2","B. 30:2","C. 10:1","D. 5:1"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The adult ratio remains 30:2 regardless of the number of rescuers. Only child and infant CPR change to 15:2 when a second rescuer is present.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c04_q02","question":"How often should the compressor role be rotated during CPR?","options":["A. Every 30 seconds","B. About every 2 minutes","C. Every 6 minutes","D. Only at the end"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Switching about every 2 minutes (every 5 cycles) prevents the decline in compression depth that fatigue causes, and the switch should take under 10 seconds.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c04_q03","question":"Once an advanced airway is in place during adult CPR, how are compressions and ventilations delivered?","options":["A. Continue 30:2 with pauses","B. Continuous compressions with 1 breath every 6 seconds","C. Stop compressions during each breath","D. 1 breath every 2 seconds"],"correct":1,"rationale":"With an advanced airway, rescuers stop pausing for breaths. They give continuous compressions and one breath every 6 seconds (about 10/min), maximizing the compression fraction.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c04_q04","question":"What is closed-loop communication?","options":["A. Speaking only to the team leader","B. Giving an order, having it repeated back, and confirming completion","C. Remaining silent to avoid distraction","D. Writing all orders down"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Closed-loop communication means the receiver repeats the order back and reports when it is done, so the leader knows tasks are understood and completed.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c04_q05","question":"When is the ideal time to perform a compressor switch to minimize interruption?","options":["A. In the middle of a compression cycle","B. During the AED rhythm analysis pause","C. During a breath","D. Randomly whenever tired"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Timing the switch to the AED rhythm-analysis pause uses a moment when compressions are already paused, so no additional interruption is added.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c04_q06","question":"Which of the following is an element of effective team dynamics?","options":["A. Vague, indirect orders","B. Clear roles and responsibilities","C. Ignoring feedback","D. Multiple leaders giving conflicting orders"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Clear roles and responsibilities is a core element of team dynamics, along with closed-loop communication, knowledge sharing, mutual respect, and constructive intervention.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c04_q07","question":"A team member notices the compressions look too shallow. What should they do?","options":["A. Say nothing to avoid conflict","B. Use constructive intervention and respectfully alert the team","C. Take over without warning","D. Wait until the code is over to mention it"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Constructive intervention means respectfully speaking up about a safety issue in real time, allowing correction that benefits the patient.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c04_q08","question":"Why does the adult ratio remain 30:2 even with multiple rescuers?","options":["A. Because adults need fewer breaths than children","B. Because pediatric arrests are more often respiratory, so children benefit from more frequent ventilation at 15:2","C. Because adults cannot tolerate breaths","D. There is no physiological reason"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Pediatric arrests are frequently respiratory in origin, so children and infants receive more frequent ventilation (15:2 with two rescuers). Adult arrests are more often cardiac, so 30:2 is retained.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c04_q09","question":"With an advanced airway in place, approximately how many breaths per minute should be given?","options":["A. 4","B. 10","C. 20","D. 30"],"correct":1,"rationale":"One breath every 6 seconds equals about 10 breaths per minute, delivered without interrupting continuous compressions.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c04_q10","question":"A two-rescuer team is doing adult CPR. Both stop and look at each other, each thinking the other is compressing. What team dynamics failure is this?","options":["A. Over-ventilation","B. Unclear roles and lack of closed-loop communication","C. Excessive compression depth","D. Correct technique"],"correct":1,"rationale":"This is a failure of clear role assignment and communication. Explicit roles and closed-loop confirmation prevent the dangerous gap where no one is compressing.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c04_q11","question":"What is the maximum time a compressor switch should take?","options":["A. 5 seconds","B. Less than 10 seconds","C. 20 seconds","D. 30 seconds"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Like all interruptions, a compressor switch should take less than 10 seconds so perfusion is minimally affected.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c04_q12","question":"The team leader's primary responsibility during resuscitation is to:","options":["A. Perform all compressions personally","B. Coordinate the team, assign tasks, and monitor CPR quality","C. Operate the AED only","D. Document the event and nothing else"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The leader maintains situational awareness, assigns and monitors tasks, ensures high-quality CPR, and adapts the plan — rather than getting fixed on one hands-on task.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c04_q13","question":"Which practice best minimizes the post-shock pause?","options":["A. Checking the pulse for 30 seconds after the shock","B. Resuming chest compressions immediately after the shock is delivered","C. Waiting to see if the patient wakes up","D. Reanalyzing the rhythm before compressions"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Compressions should resume immediately after a shock without a pulse or rhythm check, because early post-shock compressions support perfusion while the heart recovers.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c04_q14","question":"In 2-rescuer adult CPR without an advanced airway, how are the 2 breaths delivered?","options":["A. During ongoing compressions without pausing","B. During a brief pause after each set of 30 compressions","C. Continuously every 2 seconds","D. Only once at the start"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Without an advanced airway, the compressor pauses briefly after 30 compressions while the second rescuer delivers 2 breaths, then compressions resume immediately.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c04_q15","question":"Which of the following correctly pairs a scenario with its ratio?","options":["A. 2-rescuer adult → 15:2","B. 2-rescuer child → 15:2","C. 1-rescuer child → 15:2","D. 2-rescuer adult → 5:1"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Two-rescuer child (and infant) CPR uses 15:2. Adults stay at 30:2, and single-rescuer child CPR is 30:2.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c04_q16","question":"Why should ventilation be limited to about 10 breaths/min with an advanced airway?","options":["A. To conserve oxygen tanks","B. To avoid over-ventilation, which raises intrathoracic pressure and reduces cardiac output","C. Because more breaths are impossible","D. To allow the compressor to rest"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Excessive ventilation increases intrathoracic pressure and impairs venous return and cardiac output, so a controlled rate of about 10/min is used with an advanced airway.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c04_q17","question":"A well-functioning team assigns a member to watch and call out CPR quality metrics. This best reflects which element?","options":["A. Mutual disrespect","B. Knowledge sharing and reassessment/summarizing","C. Unclear roles","D. Closed airway"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Monitoring and calling out metrics supports reassessment/summarizing and knowledge sharing, helping the team maintain high-quality CPR and adjust as needed.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c04_q18","question":"During 2-rescuer adult CPR, the AED advises 'no shock' and the patient remains pulseless. What should the team do?","options":["A. Stop CPR and wait","B. Immediately resume high-quality compressions and continue the 2-minute cycles","C. Give 5 rescue breaths only","D. Remove the AED pads"],"correct":1,"rationale":"A 'no shock advised' with no pulse means resume compressions immediately and continue CPR in 2-minute cycles until the next analysis or return of a pulse.","difficulty":"Medium"}]},"c05":{"chapter":"c05","questions":[{"id":"c05_q01","question":"What should you do immediately after an AED delivers a shock?","options":["A. Check the pulse for 30 seconds","B. Resume chest compressions immediately","C. Wait for the AED to re-analyze","D. Remove the pads"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Resume compressions immediately after a shock without pausing for a pulse check, because early post-shock compressions support perfusion while the heart recovers.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c05_q02","question":"Which rhythms will an AED treat with a shock?","options":["A. Asystole and PEA","B. Ventricular fibrillation and pulseless ventricular tachycardia","C. Normal sinus rhythm","D. Sinus bradycardia"],"correct":1,"rationale":"AEDs are designed to detect and shock ventricular fibrillation and pulseless ventricular tachycardia. Asystole and PEA are non-shockable.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c05_q03","question":"What is the standard anterolateral AED pad placement in an adult?","options":["A. Both pads on the left chest","B. Right upper chest below the collarbone and left lower chest at the mid-axillary line","C. Both pads on the upper back","D. Over the stomach and the neck"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Anterolateral placement puts one pad on the right upper chest below the clavicle and the other on the left lower chest at the mid-axillary line, so current passes through the heart.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c05_q04","question":"For a 5-year-old child in cardiac arrest, which is preferred if available?","options":["A. Adult pads at full energy only","B. Pediatric (dose-attenuating) pads or a pediatric setting","C. No defibrillation for children","D. Two AEDs at once"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Children under 8 should receive pediatric dose-attenuating pads or a pediatric setting when available to reduce energy. If unavailable, adult pads are used rather than withholding defibrillation.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c05_q05","question":"Only adult pads are available for a 4-year-old in a shockable arrest. What should you do?","options":["A. Do not defibrillate","B. Use the adult pads, ensuring they do not touch (use front/back placement if needed)","C. Wait for pediatric pads to arrive","D. Cut the adult pads in half"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Defibrillation should not be withheld for lack of pediatric pads. Adult pads are used, placed so they do not touch — often anteroposterior on a small child.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c05_q06","question":"The patient was pulled from a pool and the chest is wet. What must you do before applying pads?","options":["A. Apply pads to the wet chest immediately","B. Wipe the chest dry and move the patient off standing water","C. Pour more water to improve conduction","D. Skip the AED entirely"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Water on the chest can cause the shock to arc across the skin and reduce effectiveness. Quickly dry the chest and move the patient away from standing water before applying pads.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c05_q07","question":"The patient has an implanted pacemaker with a visible bump under the right upper chest. How should you place the pad?","options":["A. Directly over the pacemaker","B. At least about 1 inch (2.5 cm) away from the device","C. Do not use the AED","D. On the pacemaker to reset it"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Place the pad at least about 1 inch from the implanted device to avoid blocking energy delivery; do not withhold defibrillation.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c05_q08","question":"There is a medication patch where a pad needs to go. What is correct?","options":["A. Place the pad on top of the patch","B. Remove the patch, wipe the area, then apply the pad","C. Leave the patch and skip that pad","D. Cut a hole in the pad"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Transdermal patches can block energy and cause burns/arcing. Remove the patch and wipe the skin before placing the pad.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c05_q09","question":"A pregnant woman is in cardiac arrest. Regarding AED use:","options":["A. Defibrillation is contraindicated in pregnancy","B. Use the AED normally — defibrillation is safe and indicated","C. Only shock at half energy","D. Wait until after delivery"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Pregnancy is not a contraindication. The best treatment for the fetus is effective resuscitation of the mother, so the AED is used normally.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c05_q10","question":"Why must everyone be 'clear' during AED analysis and shock?","options":["A. To let the patient rest","B. Contact can distort analysis and expose rescuers to the shock","C. To save battery","D. It is not actually necessary"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Touching the patient can interfere with accurate rhythm analysis and puts the rescuer at risk of receiving the shock, so the operator ensures everyone is clear both times.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c05_q11","question":"You are alone with an adult in cardiac arrest and no AED is immediately at hand. What is correct?","options":["A. Leave to search the building for an AED before starting CPR","B. Start and continue high-quality CPR; use the AED as soon as one is brought to you","C. Do nothing until an AED is found","D. Only give breaths until an AED arrives"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Do not interrupt or delay CPR to hunt for an AED when alone. Keep compressing and apply the AED as soon as one is available (ideally brought by another person).","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c05_q12","question":"The AED says 'no shock advised' and the patient has no pulse. What next?","options":["A. Remove the pads and stop","B. Immediately resume high-quality CPR","C. Repeat the analysis right away","D. Deliver a manual shock"],"correct":1,"rationale":"'No shock advised' with no pulse means the rhythm is non-shockable; resume compressions immediately and continue CPR until the next analysis or return of a pulse.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c05_q13","question":"On a small child, the two AED pads would overlap on the front of the chest. What should you do?","options":["A. Let them overlap","B. Use anteroposterior placement — one pad on the chest, one on the back","C. Use only one pad","D. Do not defibrillate"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Pads must not touch. On a small child, place one pad on the front of the chest and one on the back (anteroposterior) so they do not overlap.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c05_q14","question":"How can a team minimize the pre-shock pause?","options":["A. Stop CPR long before the shock","B. Continue compressions while the AED charges (where the device allows), then clear and shock","C. Analyze the rhythm several times first","D. Check the pulse before every shock"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Keeping hands on the chest while the device charges (when supported) shortens the pre-shock pause; the team then clears briefly to deliver the shock and resumes compressions immediately.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c05_q15","question":"Which statement about AEDs and lay rescuers is TRUE?","options":["A. Only physicians may operate an AED","B. AEDs are designed for use by lay rescuers with minimal training and give voice prompts","C. AEDs require interpreting the ECG manually","D. AEDs shock any rhythm"],"correct":1,"rationale":"AEDs analyze the rhythm automatically and guide the user with voice prompts, so lay rescuers and BLS providers can defibrillate safely and effectively. They only shock shockable rhythms.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c05_q16","question":"During AED use, when is a good time to switch compressors with no added interruption?","options":["A. In the middle of compressions","B. During the AED rhythm-analysis pause every ~2 minutes","C. During a breath","D. Never switch"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The roughly 2-minute rhythm-analysis pause is an ideal, already-occurring interruption during which to swap compressors without adding a new pause.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c05_q17","question":"What is the correct sequence of the four AED steps?","options":["A. Analyze, shock, power on, pads","B. Power on, attach pads, analyze (clear), shock if advised (clear)","C. Pads, shock, analyze, power on","D. Power on, shock, pads, analyze"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The universal order is: power on the AED, attach pads to the bare dry chest, allow analysis while clear, and deliver a shock if advised while clear — then resume CPR.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c05_q18","question":"Why should defibrillation not be delayed while retrieving or applying the AED in a witnessed shockable arrest?","options":["A. It saves paperwork","B. Survival from a shockable rhythm declines with each minute defibrillation is delayed","C. The AED battery drains quickly","D. It is only a convenience"],"correct":1,"rationale":"In shockable rhythms, the probability of survival falls substantially per minute of delay, so rapid application and use of the AED (while CPR continues) is critical.","difficulty":"Hard"}]},"c06":{"chapter":"c06","questions":[{"id":"c06_q01","question":"How should each rescue breath be delivered?","options":["A. As forcefully and quickly as possible","B. Over about 1 second, just enough to produce visible chest rise","C. Over 5 seconds with maximal volume","D. In rapid bursts"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Each breath is given over about 1 second with only enough volume to make the chest visibly rise. Larger or faster breaths cause harm through over-ventilation and gastric inflation.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c06_q02","question":"Which airway maneuver is preferred when a cervical spine injury is suspected?","options":["A. Head-tilt/chin-lift","B. Jaw-thrust without head extension","C. Hyperextension of the neck","D. No airway maneuver"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The jaw-thrust opens the airway while minimizing neck movement, making it preferred when a spinal injury is suspected.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c06_q03","question":"The E-C clamp technique is used to:","options":["A. Perform compressions","B. Maintain a mask seal while lifting the jaw during bag-mask ventilation","C. Insert an advanced airway","D. Measure oxygen"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The E-C clamp uses the thumb and index finger (C) to seal the mask and the remaining fingers (E) to lift the jaw, maintaining a good seal for bag-mask ventilation.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c06_q04","question":"Why is bag-mask ventilation usually more effective with two rescuers?","options":["A. It doubles the oxygen supply","B. One rescuer maintains a two-handed mask seal while the other squeezes the bag","C. It allows faster compressions","D. It eliminates the need to open the airway"],"correct":1,"rationale":"A two-handed seal by one rescuer greatly reduces leaks, while the second rescuer provides consistent bag volume — together delivering far more effective breaths than a one-person technique.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c06_q05","question":"What is the adult rescue-breathing rate for a patient with a pulse who is not breathing adequately?","options":["A. 1 breath every 2 seconds","B. 1 breath every 6 seconds (about 10/min)","C. 1 breath every 10 seconds","D. 30 breaths per minute"],"correct":1,"rationale":"For an adult with a pulse but inadequate breathing, deliver 1 breath every 6 seconds, about 10 breaths per minute.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c06_q06","question":"What is a consequence of excessive ventilation?","options":["A. Improved cardiac output","B. Gastric inflation and reduced venous return, lowering cardiac output","C. Lower risk of aspiration","D. Better chest recoil"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Over-ventilation raises intrathoracic pressure (reducing blood return to the heart) and inflates the stomach, increasing vomiting and aspiration risk.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c06_q07","question":"When is an oropharyngeal airway (OPA) appropriate?","options":["A. In any patient","B. Only in a patient without a gag reflex","C. Only in awake patients","D. Only in children"],"correct":1,"rationale":"An OPA is used only in patients without a gag reflex, because it can provoke gagging, vomiting, and aspiration in a patient who still has one.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c06_q08","question":"What advantage does a pocket mask have over a simple face shield?","options":["A. It requires no airway opening","B. It has a one-way valve, allows a two-handed seal, and can accept supplemental oxygen","C. It delivers compressions","D. It works without a seal"],"correct":1,"rationale":"A pocket mask provides a one-way valve for protection, a better two-handed seal, and often an oxygen inlet, making ventilation more effective and safer than a thin face shield.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c06_q09","question":"During ventilation you see no chest rise. What is the best first response?","options":["A. Squeeze the bag much harder","B. Reposition the airway and improve the mask seal, then check for obstruction","C. Give up on ventilation","D. Increase the ventilation rate"],"correct":1,"rationale":"No chest rise usually means a poor seal or an unopened/obstructed airway. Reposition the head/jaw, improve the seal, and check for a foreign body — do not simply force more air.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c06_q10","question":"Approximately what tidal volume is appropriate for adult bag-mask breaths?","options":["A. 200 mL","B. About 500–600 mL (enough for visible chest rise)","C. 1000 mL","D. As much as the bag holds"],"correct":1,"rationale":"About 500–600 mL produces visible chest rise in an adult without over-inflating; giving the full bag volume risks over-ventilation and gastric inflation.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c06_q11","question":"Is routine cricoid pressure recommended during CPR?","options":["A. Yes, always","B. No, it is not routinely recommended","C. Only in children","D. Only with a bag-mask"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Routine cricoid pressure is not recommended during CPR, as it can impede ventilation and does not reliably prevent aspiration.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c06_q12","question":"With an advanced airway in place, how is ventilation delivered?","options":["A. Pause compressions for each breath","B. Continuous compressions with 1 breath every 6 seconds","C. 1 breath every 2 seconds","D. No ventilation is needed"],"correct":1,"rationale":"With an advanced airway, compressions are continuous and breaths are given once every 6 seconds (about 10/min) without pausing compressions.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c06_q13","question":"What should be done before every ventilation attempt?","options":["A. Check blood pressure","B. Open the airway","C. Start an IV","D. Apply the AED"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The airway must be opened (head-tilt/chin-lift or jaw-thrust) before ventilating; otherwise the tongue can block airflow and breaths will not reach the lungs.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c06_q14","question":"A trauma patient needs ventilation and may have a neck injury. Which technique and device pairing is best?","options":["A. Head-tilt/chin-lift with a bag-mask","B. Jaw-thrust with a bag-mask, ideally two rescuers","C. Hyperextend the neck and use mouth-to-mouth","D. No airway opening, just squeeze the bag"],"correct":1,"rationale":"With a possible neck injury, open the airway using a jaw-thrust (minimizing neck movement) and ventilate with a bag-mask, preferably with two rescuers for a good seal.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c06_q15","question":"Which finding indicates ventilation is effective?","options":["A. The stomach distends","B. The chest visibly rises with each breath","C. Air escapes around the mask","D. The patient's abdomen rises"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Visible chest rise indicates air is reaching the lungs. Gastric/abdominal distension or air leaking around the mask indicates ineffective or misdirected ventilation.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c06_q16","question":"Under stress, a rescuer tends to squeeze the bag hard and fast. Why is this harmful?","options":["A. It has no effect","B. It causes over-ventilation and gastric inflation, reducing cardiac output and risking aspiration","C. It improves recoil","D. It increases compression depth"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Fast, forceful bagging over-ventilates the patient — raising intrathoracic pressure and inflating the stomach — which reduces circulation and increases the risk of vomiting and aspiration.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c06_q17","question":"Which adjunct is better tolerated in a patient who may still have a gag reflex?","options":["A. Oropharyngeal airway (OPA)","B. Nasopharyngeal airway (NPA)","C. Neither can be used","D. Endotracheal tube only"],"correct":1,"rationale":"An NPA is generally better tolerated than an OPA when a gag reflex may be present, as the OPA can provoke gagging and vomiting.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c06_q18","question":"During single-rescuer CPR with a pocket mask, what ventilation pattern is used?","options":["A. Continuous breaths","B. 2 breaths after every 30 compressions","C. 1 breath every 2 seconds","D. No breaths at all"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Without an advanced airway, CPR uses 30:2 — two breaths, each over about 1 second, after every 30 compressions.","difficulty":"Easy"}]}},"scenarios":{"c01":{"chapter":"c01","cases":[{"id":"c01_s01","title":"Collapse in a Shopping Mall","presentation":"You are a BLS provider walking through a shopping mall when a man in his 60s suddenly collapses. He is unresponsive and not breathing normally. A crowd gathers, and you notice an AED cabinet on the wall about 15 meters away. Two bystanders are nearby.","vitals":{"hr":"No pulse","rr":"Agonal gasps","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"Applying the Chain of Survival, what is the most appropriate immediate set of actions?","options":["A: Direct a bystander to call emergency services and another to bring the AED, and begin high-quality chest compressions now.","B: Wait for EMS to arrive before touching the patient.","C: Perform a detailed head-to-toe assessment before starting CPR.","D: Retrieve the AED yourself first, leaving the patient, before starting any compressions."],"correct":0,"explanation":"The first links of the chain are activation and high-quality CPR. Delegating the call and AED retrieval to bystanders lets you start compressions immediately without leaving the patient, compressing the time to both CPR and defibrillation.","clinicalPearl":"Delegate clearly and specifically ('You, call 911; you, bring that AED') — vague requests to a crowd often go unanswered."},{"id":"c01_s02","title":"Ward Patient Deteriorating","presentation":"On a hospital ward, a monitored patient's early-warning score rises sharply over 20 minutes: increasing respiratory rate, falling blood pressure, and new confusion. The patient still has a pulse and is breathing.","vitals":{"hr":"122 bpm","bp":"88/54 mmHg","rr":"28 bpm","spo2":"90%","loc":"Confused"},"question":"Which system-of-care action best reflects the in-hospital emphasis of the Chain of Survival here?","options":["A: Do nothing until the patient arrests, then start CPR.","B: Activate the rapid-response/medical emergency team to intervene before arrest occurs.","C: Apply an AED to the conscious patient with a pulse.","D: Begin chest compressions immediately."],"correct":1,"explanation":"In-hospital care emphasizes surveillance and prevention. Activating the rapid-response team addresses deterioration early and may prevent the arrest entirely — compressions and AED are not indicated in a patient who has a pulse and is breathing.","clinicalPearl":"The best cardiac arrest is the one that never happens — early-warning systems and rapid-response teams are the prevention link in action."},{"id":"c01_s03","title":"After the Pulse Returns","presentation":"Your team resuscitated a woman in cardiac arrest at home. After several cycles of CPR and one AED shock, she regains a pulse and begins breathing on her own. The family, relieved, asks if everything is 'over now.'","vitals":{"hr":"96 bpm","bp":"104/68 mmHg","rr":"16 bpm","spo2":"94%","loc":"Drowsy, responsive"},"question":"Based on the Chain of Survival, what is the most appropriate next step and message?","options":["A: Tell the family it is over and stop monitoring the patient.","B: Continue close monitoring, support post-arrest care and transport, and explain that recovery is an ongoing process.","C: Remove the AED pads and leave the scene.","D: Discharge the patient at home since she has a pulse."],"correct":1,"explanation":"ROSC is not the end. Post-cardiac arrest care (link 5) and recovery (link 6) continue: the patient needs monitoring, transport, and ongoing care, and the family should understand that recovery is a journey requiring further treatment and support.","clinicalPearl":"Re-arrest is common early after ROSC — keep the AED attached and reassess frequently during transport."}]},"c02":{"chapter":"c02","cases":[{"id":"c02_s01","title":"Gasping After Collapse","presentation":"A 58-year-old man collapses at his desk. You confirm the scene is safe, tap his shoulders, and shout — he does not respond. As you scan for breathing and feel for a carotid pulse, you see him take a single slow, snoring gasp every several seconds. You feel no pulse in 10 seconds.","vitals":{"hr":"No pulse felt","rr":"Occasional agonal gasp","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"What is the correct interpretation and action?","options":["A: He is breathing, so place him in the recovery position.","B: The gasps are agonal; treat as cardiac arrest and begin high-quality CPR.","C: Give two rescue breaths and recheck the pulse for 30 seconds.","D: Wait to see if the gasping becomes regular breathing."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Occasional slow, snoring gasps are agonal breathing — a hallmark of early cardiac arrest, not effective breathing. With no pulse in 10 seconds, this is cardiac arrest: begin compressions immediately.","clinicalPearl":"Agonal gasps are one of the most commonly misread signs of arrest; when in doubt, start CPR."},{"id":"c02_s02","title":"Unsafe Scene","presentation":"You arrive to find a person unresponsive on a wet garage floor near a running generator, with a faint smell of exhaust and an extension cord lying in a puddle beside them.","vitals":{"hr":"Unknown","rr":"Unknown","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"What should you do first?","options":["A: Rush in and start compressions immediately.","B: Ensure the scene is safe first — address electrical and possible carbon monoxide hazards, and move the patient/secure the scene before care.","C: Apply an AED while standing in the puddle.","D: Ignore the hazards because the patient is critical."],"correct":1,"explanation":"The scene contains electrical (cord in water) and possible carbon monoxide hazards. Making the scene safe — securing power, ensuring ventilation, and moving to a safe/dry area — must come before hands-on care to avoid a second casualty.","clinicalPearl":"A dead rescuer saves no one. Scene safety is not a delay in good care — it is the first step of it."},{"id":"c02_s03","title":"Fainted, Not Arrested","presentation":"A young woman faints at a warm outdoor event. She is briefly unresponsive when you reach her, but you confirm the scene is safe, and on assessment she is breathing normally with a strong, regular carotid pulse. She begins to open her eyes.","vitals":{"hr":"72 bpm, strong","bp":"112/70 mmHg","rr":"16 bpm, normal","loc":"Regaining responsiveness"},"question":"What is the most appropriate BLS action?","options":["A: Begin chest compressions.","B: Provide rescue breaths.","C: Monitor her, protect her airway (recovery position if needed), and reassess; call for help if she does not improve.","D: Apply an AED and analyze the rhythm."],"correct":2,"explanation":"A patient breathing normally with a strong pulse is not in cardiac arrest. Fainting (syncope) is managed by monitoring, positioning to protect the airway, and reassessing. Compressions and AED are not indicated when a pulse and normal breathing are present.","clinicalPearl":"Not every collapse is an arrest — match the intervention to the assessment findings, not to the drama of the moment."}]},"c03":{"chapter":"c03","cases":[{"id":"c03_s01","title":"Collapse on the Kitchen Floor","presentation":"A 70-year-old woman collapses at home. She is unresponsive, not breathing normally, and pulseless. You are alone, have called 911 on speaker, and are trained in CPR. She is on a tile kitchen floor.","vitals":{"hr":"No pulse","rr":"None","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"How should you perform compressions?","options":["A: Rate 60/min, depth 1 inch, hands on the upper sternum.","B: Rate 100–120/min, depth 2–2.4 inches on the lower half of the sternum, full recoil, 30:2 with breaths.","C: Continuous fast shallow compressions at 140/min.","D: Give breaths first for 2 minutes, then start compressions."],"correct":1,"explanation":"High-quality adult CPR is 100–120/min at 2–2.4 inches on the lower half of the sternum with full recoil, in a 30:2 ratio for a single trained rescuer. The firm floor is ideal for effective depth.","clinicalPearl":"Push to a 100–120 bpm tempo and let the chest fully rebound each time — depth and recoil matter as much as rate."},{"id":"c03_s02","title":"Untrained Bystander","presentation":"A man collapses on a train platform. A bystander who has never taken a CPR class is on the phone with the dispatcher. The man is unresponsive with agonal gasps and no pulse. The bystander is anxious about mouth-to-mouth.","vitals":{"hr":"No pulse","rr":"Agonal gasps","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"What should the dispatcher coach the bystander to do?","options":["A: Wait for EMS without touching the patient.","B: Perform compression-only (hands-only) CPR: push hard and fast in the center of the chest continuously.","C: Give only rescue breaths.","D: Perform 15:2 CPR with breaths."],"correct":1,"explanation":"For an adult in sudden collapse with an untrained or unwilling rescuer, compression-only CPR is recommended. Continuous hard, fast compressions maintain circulation until help arrives, and any CPR beats none.","clinicalPearl":"Removing the mouth-to-mouth barrier gets more bystanders to act — hands-only CPR saves lives."},{"id":"c03_s03","title":"Fatigue and Falling Depth","presentation":"You have been doing single-rescuer CPR for nearly 3 minutes. A feedback device shows your compressions have drifted to about 1.5 inches deep and your rate has crept up. A second trained responder has just arrived with an AED.","vitals":{"hr":"No pulse (CPR in progress)","rr":"None","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"What are the two best immediate actions?","options":["A: Keep compressing alone and ignore the device.","B: Quickly switch compressors (<10 s) to restore depth and apply the AED as soon as possible.","C: Stop CPR to rest for a minute.","D: Slow down to 60/min to regain depth."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Fatigue degrades depth within a couple of minutes. Swapping compressors quickly restores high-quality compressions, and applying the AED enables early defibrillation — both improve the chance of survival while keeping interruptions minimal.","clinicalPearl":"Feedback devices catch the silent decay of depth and rate that rescuers rarely notice themselves."}]},"c04":{"chapter":"c04","cases":[{"id":"c04_s01","title":"Second Rescuer Arrives","presentation":"You are doing single-rescuer CPR on an adult in cardiac arrest. A second trained rescuer arrives with an AED. You have completed about 2 minutes of compressions and are tiring.","vitals":{"hr":"No pulse (CPR in progress)","rr":"None","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"How should the team organize?","options":["A: Both give breaths and stop compressions.","B: Assign roles — one compresses (switch to the fresh rescuer), one manages AED/breaths — continue 30:2, and apply the AED.","C: Switch the adult ratio to 15:2.","D: Have both rescuers compress at the same time."],"correct":1,"explanation":"With two rescuers, assign clear roles and switch to the fresh compressor to maintain depth. The adult ratio stays 30:2, and the AED should be applied and used as soon as possible.","clinicalPearl":"The adult ratio never changes with more rescuers — only the workload distribution does."},{"id":"c04_s02","title":"Advanced Airway Placed","presentation":"During an adult resuscitation, a paramedic successfully inserts a supraglottic advanced airway. The team has been running 30:2.","vitals":{"hr":"No pulse (CPR in progress)","rr":"Ventilated via device","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"How should compressions and ventilations now be delivered?","options":["A: Continue pausing for 2 breaths every 30 compressions.","B: Deliver continuous compressions with 1 breath every 6 seconds (about 10/min).","C: Give 1 breath every 2 seconds.","D: Stop compressions to ventilate."],"correct":1,"explanation":"With an advanced airway, rescuers no longer pause compressions for breaths. Compress continuously at 100–120/min and ventilate once every 6 seconds (~10 breaths/min), which raises the compression fraction while avoiding over-ventilation.","clinicalPearl":"Advanced airway = asynchronous CPR: hands never stop, one breath every 6 seconds."},{"id":"c04_s03","title":"The Silent Team","presentation":"A four-person team is resuscitating an adult, but no one is calling out actions. The compressor is fatigued, the AED sits unopened, and the leader is doing compressions instead of directing. Two minutes pass with no compressor switch.","vitals":{"hr":"No pulse (CPR in progress)","rr":"Intermittent breaths","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"Which team-dynamics improvement is most needed?","options":["A: Add more rescuers regardless of roles.","B: Establish a leader who directs, assign clear roles with closed-loop communication, apply the AED, and switch the tiring compressor.","C: Everyone give breaths at once.","D: Stop CPR to discuss a plan."],"correct":1,"explanation":"The failures are unclear roles, no communication, an unused AED, and no compressor rotation. A leader who coordinates rather than compresses, clear role assignment, closed-loop communication, prompt AED use, and a timely switch will restore high-quality, organized CPR.","clinicalPearl":"A leader with their hands on the chest often loses the big picture — leading and compressing rarely mix well in a full team."}]},"c05":{"chapter":"c05","cases":[{"id":"c05_s01","title":"Shock, Then What?","presentation":"An adult in cardiac arrest has an AED attached. The AED analyzes, advises a shock, and you deliver it after confirming everyone is clear.","vitals":{"hr":"Shockable rhythm treated","rr":"None","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"What is the correct action immediately after the shock?","options":["A: Check the carotid pulse for 30 seconds.","B: Immediately resume high-quality chest compressions.","C: Re-analyze the rhythm right away.","D: Remove the pads and reassess breathing."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Compressions must resume immediately after the shock without a pulse check. Early post-shock compressions maintain perfusion while the heart reorganizes; the AED will prompt the next analysis in about 2 minutes.","clinicalPearl":"Shock, then hands back on the chest — the post-shock pause should be only a second or two."},{"id":"c05_s02","title":"Poolside Collapse","presentation":"A man collapses beside a swimming pool and is in cardiac arrest. His chest is soaked and he is lying in a thin film of water. A bystander runs up with an AED.","vitals":{"hr":"No pulse","rr":"None","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"What must you do before applying the AED pads?","options":["A: Apply pads directly to the wet chest and shock.","B: Move him to a dry area if possible and wipe the chest dry, then apply pads.","C: Pour fresh water on the chest first.","D: Do not use the AED because he is wet."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Water on the skin and standing water can cause the shock to arc and reduce effectiveness or create hazards. Move the patient to a dry surface if feasible and wipe the chest dry before applying pads — then proceed normally.","clinicalPearl":"Dry the chest and clear the puddle — a wet field wastes the shock and endangers rescuers."},{"id":"c05_s03","title":"Small Child, Adult Pads Only","presentation":"A 3-year-old is in cardiac arrest. The only AED available has adult pads and no pediatric setting. On this small chest, the two adult pads would overlap if placed side by side on the front.","vitals":{"hr":"No pulse","rr":"None","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"What is the correct approach?","options":["A: Do not defibrillate because pediatric pads are unavailable.","B: Use the adult pads with anteroposterior placement (one on the chest, one on the back) so they do not touch.","C: Overlap the pads to make them fit.","D: Wait for pediatric pads no matter how long it takes."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Defibrillation should not be withheld for lack of pediatric equipment. Adult pads are used, and on a small child they are placed front and back (anteroposterior) so they do not touch each other.","clinicalPearl":"For a small child with adult pads, go front-and-back — never let the pads touch."}]},"c06":{"chapter":"c06","cases":[{"id":"c06_s01","title":"No Chest Rise","presentation":"During CPR you attempt bag-mask breaths on an adult, but the chest does not rise and you hear air leaking around the mask. You are holding the mask with one hand.","vitals":{"hr":"No pulse (CPR in progress)","rr":"Ineffective ventilation","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"What is the best corrective action?","options":["A: Squeeze the bag much harder and faster.","B: Improve the seal (ideally a two-rescuer two-handed E-C clamp), reopen the airway, and re-attempt.","C: Stop ventilating entirely.","D: Increase the breath rate to compensate."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Air leaking with no chest rise means a poor seal or an unopened airway. Switching to a two-handed E-C clamp (with a second rescuer squeezing the bag) and reopening the airway fixes the leak far better than forcing more air, which only causes gastric inflation.","clinicalPearl":"Bag-mask is a two-person skill — a solid two-handed seal beats a hard squeeze every time."},{"id":"c06_s02","title":"Trauma Airway","presentation":"A young man is unresponsive after a fall from a ladder, with a possible neck injury. He has a pulse but is breathing inadequately and needs assisted ventilation.","vitals":{"hr":"88 bpm","bp":"124/78 mmHg","rr":"6 bpm, shallow","spo2":"89%","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"How should you open his airway and ventilate?","options":["A: Head-tilt/chin-lift and mouth-to-mouth.","B: Jaw-thrust without head extension and bag-mask ventilation, ideally with two rescuers, 1 breath every 6 seconds.","C: Hyperextend the neck to open the airway.","D: Begin chest compressions."],"correct":1,"explanation":"With a suspected cervical injury, open the airway using a jaw-thrust that avoids neck extension. He has a pulse but inadequate breathing, so provide rescue breathing at 1 breath every 6 seconds using a bag-mask — not compressions.","clinicalPearl":"Pulse present + poor breathing = rescue breathing, not compressions; suspected neck injury = jaw-thrust, not head-tilt."},{"id":"c06_s03","title":"Over-Bagging Under Stress","presentation":"A nervous new provider is bagging an intubated patient during a code, squeezing the bag rapidly about 25 times per minute. You notice the stomach is distending and the monitor shows the blood pressure generated by compressions is dropping.","vitals":{"hr":"No pulse (CPR in progress)","rr":"~25/min (excessive)","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"What should you advise?","options":["A: Bag even faster to raise oxygen levels.","B: Slow to about 1 breath every 6 seconds (~10/min) with gentle volumes to visible chest rise.","C: Stop ventilating completely.","D: Remove the advanced airway."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Rapid, forceful bagging over-ventilates the patient, raising intrathoracic pressure, reducing venous return and cardiac output, and inflating the stomach. Slowing to about 10 breaths per minute with gentle volumes restores effective circulation.","clinicalPearl":"In a code, the instinct is to bag too much — a calm 'one breath every six seconds' cadence protects the circulation."}]}},"algorithms":{"c01":{"chapter":"c01","algorithms":[{"id":"c01_alg01","title":"Universal Chain of Survival (2025) — BLS Provider View","description":"The 2025 AHA universal Chain of Survival unifies adult and pediatric, in-hospital and out-of-hospital cardiac arrest into a single six-link sequence. BLS providers own the earliest, most impactful links.","steps":["Link 1 — Activation of emergency response: recognize cardiac arrest and immediately summon help, an AED, and advanced providers.","Link 2 — High-quality CPR: begin chest compressions right away, pushing hard and fast with full recoil and minimal interruptions.","Link 3 — Defibrillation: apply an AED and deliver a shock as soon as one is available for a shockable rhythm.","Link 4 — Advanced resuscitation interventions: trained providers add airway management, medications, and treatment of reversible causes.","Link 5 — Post-cardiac arrest care: after ROSC, continue monitoring, support oxygenation and circulation, and transport to definitive care.","Link 6 — Recovery: rehabilitation, psychological support, and treatment planning for the survivor and support for the family."]},{"id":"c01_alg02","title":"System-of-Care Emphasis by Setting","description":"The universal chain is applied with different front-end emphasis depending on where the arrest occurs.","steps":["Out-of-hospital (OHCA): emphasize bystander recognition, calling for help, dispatcher-assisted CPR, and public-access AED use before EMS arrival.","In-hospital (IHCA): emphasize surveillance, monitoring, early-warning scores, and rapid-response systems to prevent arrest before it happens.","All settings: deliver high-quality CPR and rapid defibrillation, ensure smooth hand-offs between responders, and use quality improvement to strengthen the system.","Newborns: apply the separate Neonatal Chain of Care rather than the universal chain."]}]},"c02":{"chapter":"c02","algorithms":[{"id":"c02_alg01","title":"BLS Assessment & Recognition of Cardiac Arrest","description":"The stepwise sequence a BLS provider uses from arrival to the decision to start CPR.","steps":["Ensure the scene is safe before approaching; address or avoid hazards.","Check responsiveness: tap the shoulders (sole of the foot for an infant) and shout.","If unresponsive, shout for nearby help and activate the emergency response system.","Send someone to retrieve an AED and additional equipment (or use a phone on speaker if alone).","Simultaneously check for normal breathing and a pulse for no more than 10 seconds (carotid in adult/child, brachial in infant).","Interpret findings: normal breathing + pulse → monitor and reassess; pulse but inadequate breathing → give breaths; no pulse / no normal breathing / unsure → begin CPR.","If in arrest, start high-quality chest compressions immediately and apply the AED as soon as it arrives."]}]},"c03":{"chapter":"c03","algorithms":[{"id":"c03_alg01","title":"Adult 1-Rescuer BLS (CPR) Algorithm","description":"The single-rescuer sequence for an adult in cardiac arrest, following the C-A-B approach.","steps":["Verify scene safety and confirm cardiac arrest (unresponsive, no normal breathing, no pulse in ≤10 s).","Activate the emergency response system and get an AED (use a phone on speaker if alone).","Place the patient supine on a firm, flat surface and expose the chest.","Begin compressions: heel of one hand on the lower half of the sternum, other hand on top, rate 100–120/min, depth 2–2.4 inches, full recoil after each.","After 30 compressions, if trained and willing, open the airway (head-tilt/chin-lift) and give 2 breaths, each over ~1 second with visible chest rise.","If untrained or unwilling to ventilate, perform continuous compression-only CPR instead.","Continue cycles of 30:2, minimizing interruptions to less than 10 seconds.","Apply and use the AED as soon as it arrives; resume compressions immediately after any shock.","Switch compressors about every 2 minutes if another rescuer is available."]}]},"c04":{"chapter":"c04","algorithms":[{"id":"c04_alg01","title":"Adult 2-Rescuer BLS Sequence","description":"Coordinated multi-rescuer adult CPR, from role assignment through advanced-airway ventilation.","steps":["Confirm arrest and assign roles: compressor, airway/ventilation, AED operator, and team leader.","Rescuer 1 delivers compressions at 100–120/min, depth 2–2.4 inches, with full recoil.","Rescuer 2 manages the airway and gives 2 breaths during the brief pause after every 30 compressions (30:2).","Operate the AED as soon as it arrives; minimize pre-shock and post-shock pauses; resume compressions immediately after any shock.","Switch the compressor about every 2 minutes (5 cycles), ideally during AED analysis, completing the change in under 10 seconds.","When an advanced airway is placed, switch to continuous compressions with 1 breath every 6 seconds (~10/min).","Use closed-loop communication and reassess throughout; continue until ROSC or handoff to advanced care."]},{"id":"c04_alg02","title":"Elements of Effective Resuscitation Team Dynamics","description":"The behaviors that make a resuscitation team perform reliably under pressure.","steps":["Clear roles and responsibilities: everyone knows their job.","Closed-loop communication: orders are repeated back and completion confirmed.","Clear messages: concise, specific, and directed to a named person.","Knowledge sharing: information and concerns are voiced to the team.","Constructive intervention: members respectfully raise safety issues in real time.","Reassessment and summarizing: the leader re-evaluates and restates the plan.","Mutual respect: professional, supportive tone regardless of hierarchy."]}]},"c05":{"chapter":"c05","algorithms":[{"id":"c05_alg01","title":"AED Operation Sequence","description":"The universal four-step AED sequence, integrated with ongoing CPR.","steps":["Power on the AED as soon as it arrives and follow the voice prompts.","Attach the pads to the patient's bare, dry chest as shown on the pad diagrams (anterolateral or anteroposterior).","Ensure everyone is clear and allow the AED to analyze the rhythm.","If a shock is advised, confirm everyone is clear and press the shock button.","Immediately resume chest compressions after the shock (or after 'no shock advised'), without checking a pulse.","Continue CPR for about 2 minutes until the AED prompts the next analysis; use that pause to switch compressors.","Repeat analyze–shock–CPR cycles until the patient shows signs of life or advanced providers take over."]},{"id":"c05_alg02","title":"AED Special-Situation Adjustments","description":"Quick fixes for common obstacles to safe, effective pad placement.","steps":["Wet chest: move off standing water and wipe the chest dry before applying pads.","Implanted pacemaker/ICD: place the pad at least about 1 inch (2.5 cm) from the device bump.","Medication patch: remove the patch and wipe the skin, then apply the pad.","Hairy chest: press pads firmly; if they will not adhere, quickly shave the area and use fresh pads.","Small child: if pads would touch, use anteroposterior (front/back) placement.","Pregnancy: use the AED normally — defibrillation is safe and indicated."]}]},"c06":{"chapter":"c06","algorithms":[{"id":"c06_alg01","title":"Bag-Mask Ventilation Technique","description":"Steps for effective positive-pressure ventilation with a bag-mask device.","steps":["Position at the patient's head and open the airway (head-tilt/chin-lift, or jaw-thrust if spinal injury is suspected).","Select an appropriately sized mask that covers the mouth and nose without covering the eyes or extending past the chin.","Insert an airway adjunct if indicated (OPA if no gag reflex; NPA if a gag reflex may be present).","Apply the mask using the E-C clamp: thumb and index finger form a 'C' sealing the mask, the other fingers form an 'E' lifting the jaw.","Attach supplemental oxygen when available.","Squeeze the bag smoothly over about 1 second, delivering only enough volume to see the chest rise.","Match the rate to context: 2 breaths per 30 compressions (no advanced airway), or 1 breath every 6 seconds (rescue breathing or advanced airway).","If the chest does not rise, reposition the airway, improve the seal, and check for obstruction before re-attempting."]}]}},"tables":{"c01":{"chapter":"c01","tables":[{"id":"c01_t01","title":"The 2025 Universal Chain of Survival — Six Links","headers":["Link","Name","Primary Owner","BLS Provider Action"],"rows":[["1","Activation of emergency response","Bystanders / first responders","Recognize arrest; call for help and an AED"],["2","High-quality CPR","Bystanders / BLS","Push hard and fast, full recoil, minimal interruptions"],["3","Defibrillation","Bystanders / BLS","Apply AED; shock a shockable rhythm ASAP"],["4","Advanced resuscitation interventions","ALS providers","Support and hand off; assist advanced team"],["5","Post-cardiac arrest care","ALS / hospital team","Monitor, support oxygenation and circulation, transport"],["6","Recovery","Hospital / rehab / family","Support survivorship; debrief and support family"]]},{"id":"c01_t02","title":"OHCA vs IHCA — Where the Emphasis Falls","headers":["Feature","Out-of-Hospital (OHCA)","In-Hospital (IHCA)"],"rows":[["Front-end emphasis","Bystander recognition and action","Surveillance and prevention"],["Who recognizes arrest","Laypeople and first responders","Monitoring systems and staff"],["Key early tools","Dispatcher-assisted CPR, public AED","Early-warning scores, rapid-response teams"],["Goal","Fast CPR and defibrillation before EMS","Prevent arrest before it happens"]]}]},"c02":{"chapter":"c02","tables":[{"id":"c02_t01","title":"Normal Breathing vs Agonal Gasping","headers":["Feature","Normal Breathing","Agonal Gasping"],"rows":[["Rate","Regular, ~12–20/min (adult)","Slow, irregular, occasional"],["Pattern","Even, effortless chest rise","Gasping, snoring, or gurgling"],["Meaning","Adequate ventilation","Sign of cardiac arrest"],["Action","Monitor / reassess","Begin CPR"]]},{"id":"c02_t02","title":"Assessment Findings and the Correct BLS Action","headers":["Responsive?","Normal Breathing?","Pulse?","Action"],"rows":[["Yes","—","—","Monitor, reassure, get help as needed"],["No","Yes","Yes","Monitor; recovery position; reassess"],["No","No","Yes","Rescue breathing (breaths); reassess pulse"],["No","No","No / unsure","Start high-quality CPR; apply AED"]]},{"id":"c02_t03","title":"Pulse Check Site by Age","headers":["Age Group","Pulse Site","Max Check Time"],"rows":[["Adult","Carotid (neck)","10 seconds"],["Child (1 yr–puberty)","Carotid or femoral","10 seconds"],["Infant (<1 yr)","Brachial (upper arm)","10 seconds"]]}]},"c03":{"chapter":"c03","tables":[{"id":"c03_t01","title":"Summary of High-Quality CPR Components — Adult vs Child vs Infant","headers":["Component","Adult","Child (1 yr–puberty)","Infant (<1 yr)"],"rows":[["Compression rate","100–120/min","100–120/min","100–120/min"],["Compression depth","At least 2 in (5 cm), ≤2.4 in (6 cm)","At least 1/3 AP diameter (~2 in / 5 cm)","At least 1/3 AP diameter (~1.5 in / 4 cm)"],["Hand/finger placement","2 hands on lower half of sternum","1 or 2 hands on lower half of sternum","2 thumbs–encircling hands (preferred) or 2 fingers"],["Ratio (single rescuer)","30:2","30:2","30:2"],["Ratio (2+ rescuers)","30:2","15:2","15:2"],["Chest recoil","Full recoil each compression","Full recoil each compression","Full recoil each compression"],["Interruptions","Minimize; keep <10 s","Minimize; keep <10 s","Minimize; keep <10 s"]]},{"id":"c03_t02","title":"The Five Components of High-Quality Chest Compressions","headers":["Component","Target","Why It Matters"],"rows":[["Rate","100–120/min","Maintains circulation without sacrificing depth"],["Depth","At least 2 in (5 cm), not >2.4 in (6 cm)","Generates adequate blood flow; avoids injury"],["Recoil","Full recoil each time","Allows the heart to refill between compressions"],["Interruptions","Minimize, <10 s each","Blood flow falls rapidly when compressions stop"],["Ventilation","Avoid excessive ventilation","Over-ventilation reduces venous return and cardiac output"]]}]},"c04":{"chapter":"c04","tables":[{"id":"c04_t01","title":"Compression-to-Ventilation Ratio by Age and Rescuer Count","headers":["Patient","1 Rescuer","2+ Rescuers","With Advanced Airway"],"rows":[["Adult","30:2","30:2","Continuous compressions + 1 breath every 6 s"],["Child (1 yr–puberty)","30:2","15:2","Continuous compressions + 1 breath every 2–3 s"],["Infant (<1 yr)","30:2","15:2","Continuous compressions + 1 breath every 2–3 s"]]},{"id":"c04_t02","title":"Resuscitation Team Roles","headers":["Role","Main Responsibility"],"rows":[["Team leader","Coordinates the team, assigns tasks, monitors CPR quality, adapts the plan"],["Compressor","Delivers high-quality compressions; rotates about every 2 minutes"],["Airway / ventilation","Manages the airway and delivers breaths or device ventilations"],["AED operator","Applies pads, ensures safe analysis and shock, minimizes pauses"]]}]},"c05":{"chapter":"c05","tables":[{"id":"c05_t01","title":"AED Defibrillation by Age Group","headers":["Age","Preferred","If Preferred Unavailable"],"rows":[["Adult / ≥8 years","AED with adult pads","—"],["Child 1–8 years","Pediatric pads / pediatric setting","Adult pads (do not let pads touch)"],["Infant <1 year","Manual defibrillator (trained provider)","AED with dose attenuator, then AED with adult pads"]]},{"id":"c05_t02","title":"AED Special Situations","headers":["Situation","Action"],"rows":[["Wet chest / standing water","Move to dry area; wipe chest dry before pads"],["Pacemaker / ICD","Place pad ≥1 in (2.5 cm) from the device"],["Transdermal medication patch","Remove patch, wipe skin, then apply pad"],["Hairy chest","Press pads firmly; shave quickly if pads won't stick"],["Pregnancy","Use AED normally — defibrillation is safe"],["Metal jewelry","Remove only if directly under a pad"]]}]},"c06":{"chapter":"c06","tables":[{"id":"c06_t01","title":"Ventilation Rates by Situation","headers":["Situation","Breath Timing","Notes"],"rows":[["CPR, no advanced airway (adult)","2 breaths per 30 compressions","Brief pause after compressions"],["Rescue breathing, adult (pulse present)","1 breath every 6 s (~10/min)","Reassess pulse ~every 2 min"],["Rescue breathing, child/infant (pulse present)","1 breath every 2–3 s (~20–30/min)","Higher rate than adults"],["Advanced airway in place","1 breath every 6 s (~10/min)","Continuous compressions, no pause"]]},{"id":"c06_t02","title":"Airway Opening & Adjuncts","headers":["Tool / Maneuver","Use When"],"rows":[["Head-tilt/chin-lift","No suspected spinal injury"],["Jaw-thrust","Suspected cervical spine injury"],["Oropharyngeal airway (OPA)","No gag reflex"],["Nasopharyngeal airway (NPA)","Gag reflex may be present"],["Pocket mask","One- or two-rescuer ventilation with a one-way valve"],["Bag-mask device","Positive-pressure ventilation, best with 2 rescuers"]]}]}}};
